prison.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, who prosecuted gangster <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> and was the longest-tenured federal judge in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, has died of complications from surgery. He was 83. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, who died Wednesday, was one of the prosecutors who got the notorious <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> hoodlum convicted on tax-evasion charges. <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> died in 1947. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, appointed to the federal bench in 1940 by President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, rose to become chief judge in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>' northern district and twice declined a seat on the 7th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. He also was considered for a position to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` As a judge, he brought a dignity to the office that has seldom been matched,'' said <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON>. `` When you were in his courtroom, you knew you were in a courtroom.'' A New Deal liberal, he fought passionately against a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> social club that refused to admit a black federal judge and for a public defender program in the federal courts. During the stormy 1968 Democratic National Convention in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> said <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> calmed a group of protesters in his courtroom with demands for `` proper courtroom behavior.'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> retired in 1970 but continued to hear federal cases in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and for the past nine years at the federal courthouse here. Funeral services were scheduled Friday. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, five daughters and three sons.
