<HEAD>Dukakis Goes On The Attack As Bush Stays Home Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> went on the attack heading into a weekend of campaigning from the deep South to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, while Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was staying home today as the race for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approached its final two weeks. The Democratic presidential nominee, lagging behind <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the polls, was taking his case to television, both in a series of new, fiery commercials and in news interviews as he sought to raise his stock among the voters. In his television commercials, unveiled Friday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> calls <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attacks on his record `` full of lies and he knows it.'' However, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign has responded that the ads are truthful. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who has been criticized for lacking passion, appears angry in an ad titled `` Counterpunch.'' `` I'm fed up with it,'' he says as he clicks off a television set showing a `` negative'' commercial for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> commercial, showing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> riding in a tank, attacks the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor on defense issues. But <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says in his ad that both candidates want a strong defense. `` So this is n't about defense issues. It's about dragging the truth into the gutter. And I'm not going to let them do it,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, meanwhile, called for an international agreement allowing on-site inspections on demand to enforce a ban on chemical weapons. `` The eventual combination of chemical weapons and ballistic missiles could put new destructive power in the hands of governments with terrorist records,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told an audience of about 1,200 at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toledo </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention that as vice president, he cast tie-breaking votes in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 and 1986 in favor of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chemical weapon arsenals. Those votes disturbed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON>, who criticized him after the second vote and then received a call from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> explaining why her son voted as he did. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today was meeting at his home in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Valladares </PERSON>, who was freed six years ago after serving 22 years in a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> prison. <PERSON> Valladares </PERSON>, who wrote about his ordeal in the book `` Against All Hope,'' has been cited by the vice president as one of his heroes. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also planned to attend an Italian-American dinner tonight in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, too, was to attend that dinner, but his appearance was scheduled for later in the evening. The Democrat was starting his day with a joint appearance with vice presidential running mate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> before a group of pipefitters in <LOCATION> Beaumont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, before heading to a barbecue in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and then a television interview in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Later he was flying to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and then to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who was taping an interview today with <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>, has made himself available for network television interviews over the last couple of days as he seeks to seize the offensive in the remaining days of the presidential campaign. But Republican vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said the Democrats' fall in the polls is so steep, there can be no return. `` We have a strategy to win <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` Actually, I think the man from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> ... they might end up on election night maybe having a one-state strategy or maybe they'll just have a <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> strategy.''
