<FIRST>r w PM-O'Connor Bjt   10-22 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-O'Connor, Bjt,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice O'Connor Undergoes Surgery for Breast Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, the first woman on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, is recovering from surgery for breast cancer and expects to return to work in 10 days. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, 58, underwent surgery Friday at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. But few details on the procedure or follow-up treatment were provided. `` I underwent surgery for breast cancer. It was found to exist in a very early form and stage,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said in a statement released by <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>. `` The prognosis is for total recovery. I do not anticipate missing any oral arguments,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. The court is on a two-week recess and returns to hear arguments Oct. 31. The justices also will meet in private conference Oct. 28, but it was not known whether <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> will attend. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, assistant professor of medicine and director of a cancer treatment unit at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s plan for a quick return to the bench would be `` a remarkably fast recovery'' and may be good news for her prognosis. He said the speed also may indicate the cancer was caught at a very early time and there is no indication it has spread to other organs in the body. <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> is not involved in <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s case. It was not disclosed whether <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s surgery was for removal of a lump or the entire breast. There also were no details on whether the justice will receive any form of continuing treatment and when the cancer was discovered. <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> said that typically when breast cancer is detected at a very early stage, the patient can choose to have either a lumpectomy, in which only the tumor is removed from the breast, or a modified radical mastectomy, in which the entire breast is removed. Either procedure usually involves removal of the lymph glands under the arm. For a lumpectomy, patients generally are released from the hospital in three to four days, <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> said, but return in two weeks to start radiation therapy. The radiation usually is given once a day, four to five days a week, for four to six weeks. For most patients, this is a difficult period because the radiation causes fatigue. `` It would be difficult to maintain a full schedule'' while receiving radiation, said <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>. But he noted that some patients handle it much more easily than others. Patients receiving a modified radical mastectomy do not require radiation therapy and usually return to work within two to three weeks. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s operation came just a year after first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> underwent surgery to remove her left breast after laboratory tests revealed a quarter-inch cancerous lesion. Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, then 66, recovered quickly from the Oct. 17, 1987 surgery, a modified radical mastectomy. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s health, as far as is publicly known, has been good. She underwent an appendectomy in March and was soon back at work. <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justices generally jealously guard the details of their health. In 1986, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> inquired about a tremor _ a nodding motion of <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s head _ that has been apparent to court watchers for years. At times, the justice will rest her chin on her hands during the court's public oral argument sessions. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> sent back this reply through the court's public information office: `` I was unaware of such a tendency.'' As for resting her chin on her hands, she said it is `` an old and perhaps unfortunate habit.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s appointment to be a justice by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1981 ended 191 years of male exclusivity on the high court. A political and judicial conservative, she has been a champion of states' rights and enhanced police power. But while she generally sides with the conservative wing of the court anchored by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>, she has cast important moderate votes in such areas as sex discrimination and affirmative action. She was a virtual unknown on the national scene when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> picked her to replace <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, who had retired. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> served as an <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> state judge and before that was a member of that state's <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>.
