<FIRST>r a PM-FetalTissue     10-22 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetal Tissue,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Recommends Fetal Tissue Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> says it is `` acceptable'' to use the tissue from intentionally aborted fetuses in medical research. However, the panel's 13-3 vote making that fundamental finding _ the core question it was asked to decide _ carefully avoided taking a position on the morality of abortion itself or, for that matter, the morality of using the remains of planned abortions for research. `` It is of moral relevance that human fetal tissue for research has been obtained from induced abortions,'' said the draft document completed Friday. `` However, in light of the fact that abortion is legal and that the research in question is intended to achieve significant medical goals, the panel concludes that the use of such tissue is acceptable public policy.'' It went on to say that the committee position `` must not obscure the profound moral dimensions of the issue of abortion, nor the principled positions that divide scholars, scientists and the public at large. It is not the charge of this panel to attempt to settle the issue of abortion or to weigh the worthiness of competing principled perspectives on abortion itself.'' Researchers are hopeful that transplanting fetal brain cells into the brains of people with diabetes and Parkinson's disease could provide an effective treatment _ perhaps in three to five years _ and that more study could lead to similar treatments for a number of other serious diseases for which there now is no cure. The new procedure has been used experimentally on a handful of patients in other countries with promising results. The advisory committee was formed to examine moral, ethical, legal and scientific issues after <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> scientists sought permission to transplant fetal brain cells into some Parkinson's sufferers. The committee's agreement on a lengthy draft document Friday will not become final before Nov. 30, the date for submission of mail ballots on whether to adopt the exact language that will be written by <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> employees working to polish the principles adopted by the panel over five days of discussion going back to last month. In the draft version approved Friday, the panel laid out a number of recommended safeguards once research proceeds: _ `` The decision to terminate a pregnancy and the procedures of abortion should be kept independent from the retrieval and use of fetal tissue.'' _ `` Proper and informed consent should be obtained from the pregnant woman.'' _ `` Payments and other forms of remuneration and compensation associated with the procurement of fetal tissue should be prohibited, except payment for reasonable expenses occasioned by the actual retrieval, storage, preparation and transportation of the tissues.'' _ `` Potential recipients of such tissues, as well as any and all other participants, including researchers, hospital personnel and other service-providers, should be properly informed as to the source of the tissues in question.'' The panel also concluded that donations of fetal tissue to a family member or acquaintance for medical purposes should be banned to discourage women from becoming pregnant with the intention of having an abortion and donating the tissue to a sick relative or close friend.
</TEXT>
