<HEAD>TVA Charged With Violating NRC Regulations Through False Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Repeated false statements by the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear program constitute a violation of federal regulations by the <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> charges. However, the commission said it has decided not to take action on the original statements by <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. White, a former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear submarine program, `` as a matter of prosecutorial discretion.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> also decided, according to a letter sent Friday to <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Runyon </PERSON>, not to assess a fine because `` a civil penalty for this matter is not necessary to further focus the attention of either <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> or the industry on the importance of complete candor'' in dealing with the commission, the letter said. The <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement read by spokeswoman <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>, defended White while praising the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s decision not to assess a fine. `` We continue to believe that Admiral <PERSON> White </PERSON> did not intend to mislead the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> on this or any other matter,'' the statement said. `` We are pleased that the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> did not fine <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> upon completion of this investigation,'' according to the statement. `` However, we are disappointed that <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> received a notice of a violation on statements relating to Appendix B. ... The <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> board is fully committed to operating a safe and reliable nuclear power program.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s letter said the <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> has 30 days to admit or deny the allegations and to show what corrections it has undertaken if the charge is admitted. The case concerns a March 1986 letter <PERSON> White </PERSON> wrote to the commission. White had been hired a few months earlier to shape up <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>'s nearly collapsed nuclear effort that had seen the closure of five reactors. <PERSON> White </PERSON> wrote the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> that there had been `` no pervasive breakdown of the quality assurance program'' at the Watts Bar plant under construction near <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn </LOCATION>. He repeated that assurance in a follow-up letter and in statements to <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> investigators, adding that he had received a review of the program by outside experts. In fact, according to previous commission testimony to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and according to Friday's letter, <PERSON> White </PERSON> had not even spoken with seven of the nine people he identified as constituting the outside review group, and the two people he did speak with had not reviewed <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>'s quality assurance efforts but had only given opinions of the work of an earlier in-house group. `` No one identified by Mr. <PERSON> White </PERSON> as being a member of the second group understood there to be such a group,'' the letter said. In April, <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s Office of Investigations testified before a congressional panel that White was playing word games. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> told the investigations subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> White </PERSON> apparently was intending `` pervasive'' to mean `` 100 percent.'' While technically true, <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>'s quality assurance had serious and widespread problems, he said. At the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> staff, an internal group headed by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, assistant executive director for operations, concluded that White's statements were not deliberately false The matter was referred to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which has refused to comment on the status of the case. White has denied any wrongdoing and has been supported by the <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> board. He is retiring in January. The letter, signed by <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, now deputy executive director for regional operations, said the violation was being assessed even though White is leaving because `` <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> management as a whole is responsible for the quality of communications with the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` Both the individuals involved and the organization must share responsibility for the actions giving rise to these violations, but the fundamental premise of our regulatory system makes <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>, as the licensee, ultimately responsible,'' the letter said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> must be confident that it can rely on the information furnished by a licensee,'' the letter said. `` ... Anything less than accurate and complete statements to the commission can not and will not be tolerated.''
