<HEAD>Quayle Sees ``One State Strategy'' For Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Democratic slide in the polls is so steep that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> could be left with a `` one state strategy'' on election day, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. And as he stumped through the South on Friday, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> worked to steal a line his Democratic counterpart used to devastating effect in the vice presidential debate. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, he declared, `` is no <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>'' and wo n't be making a comeback. A confident-sounding <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said there's a sharp contrast between Republican and Democratic election strategies. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told college students in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> that the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> has a `` 50-state strategy'' and made light of reports that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is narrowing his focus to about 18 states with enough electoral votes for a win. `` We have a strategy to win <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` Actually, I think the man from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> ... they might end up on election night maybe having a one-state strategy or maybe they'll just have a <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> strategy.'' The quip that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` is no <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>'' comes straight from Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> who scored the premier moment of the vice presidential debate when he told <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, `` You're no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> described a conversation between <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and his father, a former senator. `` I guess he -LRB- Gore Jr. -RRB- called home and talked to his dad, when his father told him that this reminded him of the <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> campaign in 1948,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` Let me tell you something, I do n't know <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, I never served with <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is not a good friend of mine. `` But I know this: <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is no <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> used precisely that cadence in setting up <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> for his debate zinger, and aides said Friday's speech was the first time <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> had referred to the put-down in a campaign appearance. Republican presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had also set the stage when he used a similar line in a self-deprecating fashion during a dinner in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Thursday night. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> insisted the comparison was apt because many were `` trying to compare the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign to the <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> campaign.'' <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> was perceived to be trailing throughout the 1948 campaign, but ended up defeating Republican <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>. Most polls show the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> ticket this year with a persistent lead, and <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> insisted there will be no comeback this time around. During his Southern swing, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> spoke to the college students in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> at a noisy rally where critics and backers competed for attention, repeatedly interrupting the candidate. `` They've always been negative and they always will be,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` They are the party of failure. We are the party of success. `` They can go ahead and yell,'' he said. `` We're going to talk about issues and ideas.'' Throughout his Southern swing, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> took a tough stance against a tax increase and in favor of defense as he courted conservative voters in a region where most polls suggest <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is strong. At a flag-waving riverside rally in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> made a frank appeal for backing from conservative southern Democrats. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, he argued, is `` not in the southern Democratic tradition of national defense. Disenchanted Democrats are fed up with liberalism.'' He got some cheering news from the crowd, including one sign which read `` Thank God Quayle is no JFK.''
