<HEAD>Officials: Never Promised Marcos Anything</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Marcos Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Indicted former Philippine President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> received no promises from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials to persuade him to leave his country without bloodshed during a popular, military-based revolt in 1986, officials say. More than 2 -LCB- years after he fled the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, and six others were indicted Friday on racketeering charges involving a vast fortune the Marcoses allegedly stole from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Action by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a federal appeals court and the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government opened the final doors to that indictment which came in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investigation that began shortly after <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was airlifted to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in February 1986. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> official in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> who was <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> liaison with <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> during his first three months of Hawaiian exile, said Friday that no high official, including President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, made any promises to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. `` We offered refuge because the prospect of violence threatened him and his family and to avoid a very bloody confrontation in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Belize </LOCATION>, where he is now the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador. `` There is no indication that anyone at high levels offered anything inappropriate.'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> claims in a lawsuit filed in <LOCATION> Honoluu </LOCATION> that he was deceived into leaving his country against his will. The case against <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> has involved discussions with <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> officials and months of dealings among the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Both State and <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> department sources confirmed that there were disagreements over how to handle the case, with <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> wanting to indict prior to plea bargaining with <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and State urging a pre-indictment attempt to bargain. A plea bargain which <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> rejected was described by one official as an attempt to get <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return his vast wealth to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, which is the main objective of the case. The government of President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> alleges that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his associates took out of the country $ 5 billion to $ 10 billion, much of it stashed in Swiss banks. The way was cleared for the indictment after a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> announcement Thursday that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would `` not prevent the law from taking its course.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> later said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was saddened by the court action because <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was a friend. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had invited <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and administration officials were concerned about the impact the indictment would have on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> credibility in dealing with foreign rulers in the future. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> sai