<HEAD>Congress Passes Bill Reforming Distribution of Disaster Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bill reforming the way the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> distributes aid after natural disasters has been approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and sent to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for his signature. The Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Amendments of 1988 had their roots in the government's response to tornadoes that raced through <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> before hitting <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> on May 31, 1985, killing 90 people. Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridge </PERSON>, R-Pa., authored the bill after complaining that the help offered by <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 failed to meet the needs of residents and municipalities facing major repairs At a hearing on the bill last year, Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., said reform was necessary because <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> `` has gained the notoriety of being very cumbersome and tortuous for the citizens of this nation to understand. The bill died in the 99th Congress, was introduced again last year, and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> finally passed it in the spring. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a companion bill by voice vote Friday. Since the measure was slightly different from the version the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had passed earlier, it was sent back to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which approved it Friday night. The legislation was sent to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who was expected to sign it. Among other reforms, the bill would bar <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> from paying less than a 75 percent share of aid to local governments qualifying for public repair projects following a disaster. It would add guidelines to speed the distribution of post-disaster aid and would permit federal funds to be used for the first time for local projects designed to lessen the effect of disasters before they strike. The measure also would make temporary housing assistance through <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> available for up to 18 months, six months longer than under the current system. Originally, the measure was opposed by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, which said its initial price tag _ $ 15 to $ 20 million per year above what <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> pays now _ was too high. But the bill's cost was trimmed down to zero by eliminating some administrative expenses and by asking state and local governments to share some of the cost of aid in a federally declared emergency, among other changes.
