<HEAD>Lagerfeld Shows Longer Skirts, Merry Widow Waistlines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Merry widow corset effects gave definition to <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagerfeld </PERSON>'s summer ready-to-wear collection. But even with these ribbed waistlines, his show was full of softness, a new note on the fashion scene. The new, easy clothes were appealing, but lacked the firm dynamics that the fashion world has come to expect of <LOCATION> Lagerfeld </LOCATION>. Most of the clothes shown Friday were nice without being sensational. A lot of pants, very straight and not too wide, looked excellent in off-white topped by deep rose or dusty green blazers. Seen on soft green jersey dresses, the merry widow touch of ribbed seams was a detail that never cinched the waist in. Another option was pinstriped trouser suits, and high hats gave them trouser suits a raffish, 19th century charm. A few short skirts cropped up, notably in some white knit `` tennis'' style dresses with red or green stripes at hem and turtle neck. But they were just a few inches above the knee. <LOCATION> Lagerfeld </LOCATION> announced long ago that longer skirts were coming in, and he sees that they do, showing most skirts way below knee level. With a few pastels and plenty of black and white in linens, knits and cottons, the effect was nearly subdued. For those who love knits and do n't want the ribbed corset effect, a lot of easy pleated midcalf skirts were belted near the hip with wide and handsome belts with gobby metal decor. <PERSON> Lagerfeld </PERSON> played around with jackets, making some hems in tulip shapes, belting others, cutting out some fitted numbers with rounded decolletes. Coat dresses at <LOCATION> Lagerfeld </LOCATION> were long and full, almost ending up looking like housecoats in a wallpaper flower print. The navy wool crepe full-skirted coat dress was topped by a big organdy bow _ also added to a simple but easily-cut trouser suit. <PERSON> Lagerfeld </PERSON> also came up with an excellent suite of tiered and pleated ivory crepe de chine numbers with fullish leg o' mutton sleeves and wide brown belts. The evening wear was sparse but did feature some fitted and full-skirted dresses, some with chiffon halter necklines and skirts, others with long, fitted torsoes in black lace and white pique. Easy-to-wear was also the idea at <PERSON> Popy </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreni </PERSON>, an Italian-born designer who has been showing in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> for several years now. Her clothes were often based on gray _ in full shiny wool trench coats, in wool and silk trouser suits and dresses with full skirts. The overall effect was always girlish. To contrast with all the gray, lilac and yellow also came out in wide knit culotte suits or paired with charcoal in draped tops. With details like jabots on pinstriped shirt-jackets, or full skirts under fitted torsoes, the clothes were feminine and young. For the sporty set, <PERSON> Moreni </PERSON> also showed a line of striped wide Bermudas and shorts. The dressy touch here was also disarmingly girlish in a series of long-skirted ivory silks and a big line of white cottons with ruffles and tiers that looked like simplified versions of 18th century frilliness. For garden parties or dressy barbecues, the pretty flowered chiffon dresses or multicolored rainbow numbers had unsophisticated charm. Like all of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Perris </PERSON> showed plenty of pants, from buttoned, tight toreador style to the widest pyjamas. His lines were always soft, but jackets for long skirts and trousers were cut with big wing lapels and swallow-tails. The color scheme was subdued, with soft pearl gray and pastels in light wools, cotton and silks. Even the boleros were waist-nipped, and while the emphasis was on dressier clothes, <PERSON> Perris </PERSON> also brought out wide street shorts with cuffs and spencer jackets.
</TEXT>
