 <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Isbell </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> founder, died Thursday at the age of 83. In 1954, <PERSON> Isbell </PERSON> and a group of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> investors began buying motels. In 1960 he decided to assemble the motels into a chain owned by a publicly held company, and two years later became chairman of a 63-motel chain known as <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Under his leadership, <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inns </ORGANIZATION> expanded to 500 motels in 45 states, and later into <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and overseas. <PERSON> Isbell </PERSON> ran the <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> chain as president and chief executive officer until 1973 and retired as chairman in 1979.
