<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUNTA GORDA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man's wedding night turned into the jailhouse blues when a deputy who performed the marriage returned to arrest him. <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Clough </PERSON>, bride-to-be of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, recruited Sheriff's Deputy <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, who's also a notary public, to conduct Thursday's ceremony `` I thought it would be a really nice idea,'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. `` This would be a nice change of pace, I told myself, and I'd be helping these two kids out.'' At <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s home, <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said he thought <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> looked familiar. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 18, explained that the deputy had ticketed him in the past. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> put that out of his mind and performed his first wedding. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s explanation stuck in the back of his mind, <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. `` I ran a computer check on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and I could n't believe it when it came back,'' the deputy said. `` He had three outstanding warrants pending, for what else _ failing to show up in court on the tickets I wrote him.'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> turned his patrol car around and arrested <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` I almost wished I had any other job in the world but the one I had,'' the officer said. After spending his wedding night in jail, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was released on bond Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Winton </PERSON>, an adjunct professor at <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continuing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, teaches basic physics to adult, part-time students who could n't care less about the subject. `` They're mostly business majors. This is their required science credit. So I try to add a little pizazz,'' he said. The pizzaz works. Total strangers have turned up in class just to gawk at the magic tricks <PERSON> Winton </PERSON> employs to make physics exciting. His first trick is a variation of the old whisk-the-tablecloth-off-a-set-table trick. He stacks up four glasses of water, a cookie sheet, four cardboard tubes and four jumbo eggs. `` The secret is jumbo eggs. They're heavier, so they have more inertia,'' <PERSON> Winton </PERSON> says. When the cookie sheet is knocked away, the eggs drop into the glasses because, as <PERSON> Winton </PERSON>'s students know, bodies at rest want to stay at rest and bodies in motion want to stay in motion. He demonstrates the importance of velocity by driving a large nail into a piece of plywood with his hand wrapped in a towel. His grand finale is lying on a bed of nails and having a trained volunteer smash cinder blocks with a sledgehammer, first on his abdomen, then on his forehead. The laws of physics offer protection, but no guarantees. Raw knuckles, a bruised hand, a scraped scalp and a mild concussion sometimes are part of the act. `` I've had students who could n't bear to look,'' <PERSON> Winton </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
