<HEAD>Dozens Killed In Clashes With Rebel Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Clashes this month between the army and guerrillas left 56 soldiers and 30 rebels dead, state-run <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> reported. The broadcast Friday said the highest death toll _ 21 soldiers and 18 rebels _ was in the <LOCATION> Shan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, one of many areas of the country plagued by an insurgency by ethnic groups demanding greater regional autonomy. The 83 clashes with `` various rebel groups'' Oct. 1-21 left 110 government troops wounded and six others missing, the radio said. A government spokesman earlier said that from Sept. 26 to Monday, 35 government soldiers were killed and 95 wounded in those battles, which are continuing. He said rebel casualities were believed to be heavy. Friday's announcement mentioned only two troops and three rebels killed in <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> State </PERSON>. The guerrilla groups have been fighting the government for the past four decades. The government also has acknowledged that besides the insurgents, its troops killed more than 450 people since Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> seized power in a coup Sept. 18. Western diplomats say the victims included large numbers of people peacefully demanding democracy, but the government says most were looters and other `` destructive elements.'' While banning pro-democracy demonstrations, <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>'s administration has allowed formation of opposition parties and promised a general election sometime next year The radio said four more parties registered Friday, bringing the number of officially recognized parties to 32. The four new parties included two parties of the Chin minority group _ the <ORGANIZATION> Zomi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>. Four other minority-based parties registered earlier. The broadcast added that announcements will be made later on the registration of a dozen more parties.
