<HEAD>Malaysian Looking To Indonesia For A Rhino Mate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> is looking for a country willing to loan it a male <LOCATION> Sumatran </LOCATION> rhinoceros so it can mate the rare species with its seven females, wildlife officials said today. <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s only male <LOCATION> Sumatran </LOCATION> rhino still has not reached maturity, said environment minister <PERSON> Law </PERSON> <PERSON> Hieng </PERSON> <PERSON> Ding </PERSON>. The rhinos would be bred at the Ayer Keroh Zoo in <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION>, 90 miles south of here and the <ORGANIZATION> Sungai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dusun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Selangor </LOCATION>, about 30 miles from here. The department is looking into the possibilities of acquiring the rhino under its animal exchange program with <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and other neighboring countries which may have the endangered species, Law said.
