<DATELINE>BRIDGETON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> announced a tentative agreement Friday on a new labor contract for 17,500 workers in five states. Bargainers had been working against an 11 p.m. Friday strike deadline on an agreement for union workers at <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> plants in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> cities of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION>, the only union locals that had not previously reached a tenatative settlement. Details of the agreements were not immediately released. Earlier Friday, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 2096 of <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, with 648 members, announced it had reached a tentative agreement. <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> was the fourth <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> local to reach a tentative agreement with the <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, Ill.-based <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest maker of earthmoving equipment. Contract talks started Aug. 4. Union officials had said those locals without a tentative agreement by the 11 p.m. deadline would be authorized to call a strike. Minutes before the strike deadline, the <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> local reached a tentative agreement, said <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> negotiator <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> local followed suit about an hour later. Union sources earlier said a special job classifications was the main snag in talks with the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> locals in <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION>. Those three locals represent 14,400 of <PERSON> Catepillar </PERSON>'s 17,500 <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> workers. After months of bargaining and two contract extensions, both sides announced Thursday that a tentative agreement had been reached on nearly every key issues, including pay raises and improved health and pension benefits. The locals had objected to the creation of a special job classifications for highly technical jobs because they said it threatened the union's traditional seniority system. Workers trained to fill these high-tech positions could not be bumped from their jobs by untrained workers with more seniority who faced layoff. Company officials maintained, however, that management could not afford to invest in new automated machinery and specialized job training unless it could depend on having those workers remain on the job. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> locals in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, earlier reached tentative agreements and the <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, plant is being closed.
