<FIRST>u i PM-Sakharov     10-22 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sakharov,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Physicist Credits Recent Reform For Travel Permit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet dissident <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> says the government's approval of his first foreign trip, with visits to as many as six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities next month, is a result of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s recent reforms. The 67-year-old physicist who spent eight years in exile in his own country for human rights campaigning, told a Friday news conference that authorities agreed `` in principle'' to the trip but have not yet issued travel documents. `` I consider that the positive response making my trip possible stems from the very big changes in our country during the last few years,'' said <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, who won the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize for his human rights activities. The lifting of the travel ban against <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, father of the Soviet dissident movement, marked another reversal in <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> policy by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who has liberalized Soviet society on many fronts. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said he plans to attend a meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of a philanthropic group called the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanity </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> is to attend the foundation's board meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Nov. 15-16 and meetings in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and possibly <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said group member <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodgman </PERSON>. The foundation was set up in January to help solve environmental, human rights, disarmament and economic development problems. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> welcomed the Soviet decision but urged <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to give the same permission to all Soviets wishing to travel abroad. `` Soviet use of alleged knowledge of state secrets to deny many other Soviet citizens the right to travel abroad is deplorable and inconsistent with Soviet commitments under the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Accords,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s trip could set an uncomfortable precedent. Hundreds of citizens have been denied permission to travel abroad on grounds they know state secrets. He had been denied permission to travel on grounds he had access to sensitive information while working on the Soviet hydrogen bomb in the 1950s. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> has spoken out repeatedly for free emigration and protested the Soviet intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1979. He was exiled to the closed city of <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION> in 1980 and released under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s administration in December 1986. In another sign of his return to good graces of Soviet officials, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was elected one of 47 members to the ruling Presidium of the prestigious academy. During the now-disgraced rule of President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, some academy members tried to expell <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said the academy voted 152-82 to elect him to the Presidium, its leading body. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> now is conducting research in cosmology, the study of the universe's origin. The physicist said his wife, <PERSON> Yelena </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON>, would not travel with him but will travel later to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> alone for medical treatment.
</TEXT>
