<FIRST>u w PM-TaxBill     10-22 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Approves Tax Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congress today completed action on a bill cutting taxes by $ 4.1 billion and increasing the clout of individuals involved in disputes with the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. With only a half-dozen members on the floor, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved the bill by voice vote and sent it to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who, backers predict, will sign it. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had endorsed the compromise a few hours earlier on a 395-1 vote. `` There are thousands and thousands and thousands of people who are going to be beneficiaries and they'll thank us for doing our job,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. Those thousands include farmers, who will be relieved of paying the federal tax on diesel fuel used for off-road purposes and will no longer have to fret with the paperwork caused by the `` heifer tax'' on livestock. Other winners include owners of mutual funds, free-lance writers, workers who receive tuition payments from their employers and families saving for a child's college education. But taxes on other groups will have to go up by $ 4.1 billion over three years to pay for the $ 4.1 billion of selected tax cuts. The losers include pipe smokers, who, for the first time, will have to pay a tax of 45 cents on a pound of their favorite smoking mix; anyone accustomed to writing off part of their basic home phone charge; investors in single-premium life insurance policies, and some corporations, especially those owned by native Alaskans. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> corporations would lose a special benefit that has allowed them to sell operating losses to profitable companies. Lawmakers say the provision has been abused. Negotiators who drafted the final legislation accepted most of the `` taxpayer's bill of rights,'' written chiefly by Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>., which is aimed at tipping the scales slightly more toward taxpayers when they face audit or collection actions by the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> These provisions were approved in response to a growing concern among many lawmakers about isolated reports of taxpayers being harassed and intimidated by some <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employees. In the future, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> would have to fully inform taxpayers of their rights and recourses before any audit or collection steps are taken. The agency would have to give a 30-day notice, compared with 10 days in current law, before seizing property to pay back taxes, and it would be barred from promoting employees on the basis of how much money they collect. The legislation, more than two years in the making, was designed originally to clear up typographical errors and ambiguous wording in the big tax overhaul enacted in 1986. It grew in size as the tax-writing committees tacked on amendments extending some expiring provisions and granting tax benefits for selected groups. A major non-tax provision seizes 540 acres of land adjacent to the <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Battlefield </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> to block construction of a shopping mall on the site. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration opposes this provision, although there has been no indication whether it would prompt a veto. Negotiators, meeting behind closed doors, dropped another unrelated provision, which would have imposed economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to protest that nation's use of poison gas against some of its Kurdish citizens. Major provisions would: _ Exempt from tax interest earned on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings bonds that are redeemed to pay for college, starting Jan. 1, 1990 _ Extend expiring tax benefits to help lower-income families buy their first home; reward businesses for increased spending for research and experimentation, and boost incentives for investment in low-income rental housing _ Renew an expired provision that allows workers to exclude from income tuition payments made by their employers; most graduate study would not qualify _ Extend an exclusion for the value of employer-financed legal-service benefits _ Prohibit a business deduction for the basic monthly cost of a home telephone _ Allow free-lance writers, artists and photographers to deduct certain expenses before a project starts producing income _ Permit owners of mutual funds to deduct certain operating expenses of the fund without having to meet a requirement that only miscellaneous expenses exceeding 2 percent of income be deducted The single House vote against the bill was cast by Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
