<HEAD>Hirohito's Anemia Lessens, But Kidneys, Liver Worsen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Larger-than-usual blood transfusions in recent days have improved Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s anemia, but court officials said today that his kidney and liver functions are worsening. Doctors have stopped using antibiotics to treat the 87-year-old monarch's infected bile duct, said <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said only that physicians `` believed it was necessary to do so,'' but news reports quoted palace sources as saying the infection had declined and doctors were concerned about side effects from prolonged use of strong drugs. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> received another transfusion of 0.4 of a pint Friday night, <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said. That brought the total he has been given since his condition worsened on Sept. 19 to 24 pints _ nearly three times as much as is normally in his body. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> quoted unnamed palace sources as saying the emperor's liver functions were worsening and that the nitrogen level in his blood was three times above normal. Palace officials said the emperor had not discharged any blood for two days, but doctors believed his internal bleeding was continuing.
