<HEAD>Hershiser Sings Hymn on Johnny Carson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Orel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hershiser </PERSON>, appearing on `` The Tonight Show starring <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>,'' sang a few bars from the hymn he said lifted his spirits when the pressure was on during the World Series. On the urging of <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> and Friday's studio audience, <PERSON> Hershiser </PERSON> warbled `` Praise God, from whom all blessings flow ... Praise Father, Son and Holy Ghost.'' The Christian hymn, known as the Doxology, dates back to 1695 and is based on text from Psalm 150. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>, who appeared to be somewhat embarrassed and moved, said, `` That's very sweet.'' The audience responded with sustained applause. <PERSON> Hershiser </PERSON> said he sung the hymn on the mound on Thursday as he pitched the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION> to victory over the <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletics </ORGANIZATION> in the fifth and deciding game of the World Series, which the <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION> won four games to one. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Hershiser </PERSON>, winner of the most valuable player awards in this year's World Series and National League Championship Series, what his future plans are. `` Retirement,'' the 30-year-old pitcher quipped.
