<HEAD>Students Firebomb USO Facility After U.S. Soldiers And Koreans
Brawl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty students hurled firebombs at a USO building after a brawl between <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers, police and news reports said today. No injuries were reported in the attack Friday night on the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, a recreational body for American soldiers based overseas. There also were no damages, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military authorities said, even though one firebomb cleared a fence but missed the building. Guards immediately put out the blaze without incident, the authorities said. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> newspapers said the attack involved 20 slogan-chanting students who hurled about 10 firebombs at the American facility and scattered leaflets demanding the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government apologize for assaults by American soldiers on Koreans. One American soldier and three Koreans were injured last Sunday in a fight involving about 40 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers and 200 Koreans in <LOCATION> Itaewon </LOCATION>, a shopping district close to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military headquarters in southern <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Radicals recently stepped up an anti-U.S. campaign in the aftermath of the Olympics Games, when the actions and manners of some American athletes and the allegedly biased coverage of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> media during the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 games upset many Koreans Dissidents demand the withdrawal of about 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a mutual defense pact, contending the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> hampers unification of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. The peninsula was divided into the communist North and the capitalist South in 1945, at the end of World War II. In another development, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy has asked <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials and athletes taking part in the International Paralympics Games in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to refrain from going to <LOCATION> Itaewon </LOCATION> at night, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. Signs were posted in living quarters of American athletes, but the embassy gave no explanation, they said. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team, said the embassy has asked his team not to wear clothes or uniforms identifying nationality during the visit to Itaewon.
