<HEAD>Whale Rescue Effort Brings Boom to Barrow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARROW, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This community above the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>, the northernmost in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, hardly qualifies as a popular fall destination with its below-zero weather, fog and the occasional polar bear roaming the streets. But the drama of efforts to free three ice-trapped whales has turned the Eskimo village into a boom town. `` It feels like this is Grand Central station,'' said <PERSON> Fran </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, owner of <PERSON> Pepe </PERSON>'s North of the Border Restaurant, where business in the past week has been up 20 percent. Hordes of journalists from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> have come to report on the plight of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> gray whales, imprisoned under <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> ice about 13 miles northeast of here for more than two weeks. One of the whales disappeared under the ice Friday and was presumed dead. Residents of this whaling village of about 2,200 people are more accustomed to visits from polar bears that occasionally wander in off the ice pack. But they are taking the attention and the demands of the media in stride. `` We've become something of a nerve center,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, manager of the Top of the World Hotel. The 40-room hotel has been fully booked since Oct. 16, and its switchboard has been lit up constantly with calls from people seeking rooms and information about the whales. Another 16-room hotel and all 60 rooms at the former <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> also were filled, <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> said. `` Right now, we're taking the names of people in town who have space, and we're referring callers to them,'' <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> said. `` It's all part of the community's response, but we're glad to do it. The impact has spread far beyond the hotels. A special bank of phones was installed in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Slope </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Borough </LOCATION> assembly's chambers Thursday to improve communications, said <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> of the borough's information liaison office. Phone lines in the borough's search-and-rescue operations center had gotten so clogged the rescue squad could n't have received emergency calls had there been any, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said. And there is n't a rental vehicle left in town. Enterprising natives are hitching sleds to their snowmobiles to haul reporters, photographers and TV crews across the ice to view the whales. Some reporters went to the operations center to hitch rides to the ice pack on borough and military helicopters involved in the rescue effort, but the center was declared off-limits. Ill-equipped visitors, unfamiliar with the harsh Arctic conditions, have created a run on insulated boots, stocking caps, mittens and other cold-weather gear. Journalists also like to eat well. `` They're bigger spenders because they're on expense accounts,'' said <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, who bills her establishment as `` the farthest <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> restaurant.'' Asked if she thought the media response was out of proportion to the situation, <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said, `` Well, maybe just a little bit. But what's wrong with caring?'' <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said the coverage will show the compassion the Eskimos feel for whales despite their hunting heritage. The Eskimos hunt bowhead whales, not <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> grays.
