<HEAD>Carlucci Says More Weapons Would Bring Peace To Mideast </HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HN1 of Oct. 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> says Americans must get over their fear of selling arms to Arab countries, or risk losing ground to other countries with the weapons and the will to step in. `` <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and others are moving into the highly desirable positions of confidence and influence which <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has traditionally enjoyed with friends such as <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` I see tens of billions of dollars worth of jobs going abroad instead of sustaining our key defense industries and bolstering the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. economy.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, speaking Friday at an American-Arab relations seminar at <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the threat to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would be greater if <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> countries look to other nations to supply arms. `` The notion that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense cooperation with moderate <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states poses a danger to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is ill-founded and untrue,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> must regard non-American arms in the hands of its neighbors as a higher risk.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has rejected major arms sales to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> warned lawmakers that the denial poses a greater threat militarily in the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> and economically in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Fouad </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Farsy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s deputy minister of information, said earlier in the seminar that his country, like other moderate neighbors of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, should not be treated as the enemy due to its longstanding relationship with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` In the last 15 years, in the development of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, we have looked to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for leadership, guidance ... and manpower,'' <PERSON> Al-Farsy </PERSON> said. The international president of B'nai B'rith, a Jewish civic and fraternal organization, said the group was dismayed to hear that <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> `` defined <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> arms sales policy in terms of dollars and cents. `` If the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wanted primarily to earn monetary profit on weapons sales, this country could sell arms to all sorts of dictatorial and totalitarian regimes around the world,'' said <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> <PERSON> Reich </PERSON>. `` However, the cornerstone of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms sales policy has always been to examine first and foremost the strategic and moral implications of military sales,'' <PERSON> Reich </PERSON> said. `` In the case of arms sales to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has always chosen the wise course of supporting its most reliable ally in the region, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Reich </PERSON> said. `` This has meant, and rightly so, denying sophisticated weapons to those nations who _ in defiance of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign policy which seeks advancement of the peace process _ continue to declare themselves to be in a state of war with <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s steadfast partner in strategic cooperation, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and <PERSON> Al-Farsy </PERSON> agreed on the need for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to meet face-to-face to negotiate peace in the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION>, but had differing conditions for how to get them talking. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> first needs to renounce terrorism and agree that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has a right to exist. `` Palestinian participation is required at every stage of negotiations concerning the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, since the outcome will affect their interests and will bear directly on their future as a people,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` Without their active participation, no agreement can be expected to endure.'' <PERSON> Al-Farsy </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not set itself up as an `` honest broker'' then take <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s side on every question. `` There can be no chance for peace if one side will not talk to the other. To them, progress is the lack of progress,'' <PERSON> Al-Farsy </PERSON> said of the Israelis. `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is stubborn because it knows the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will support her no matter what position she takes.''
