<HEAD>Texas State Fair Shoot-Out Leaves One Dead, Three Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT G. WIELAND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A shootout on the midway of the State Fair left one dead and three wounded, including a police sergeant who was shot in the hand as he grappled with gunman, authorities said today. Two other officers were hurt in scuffles, and numerous bystanders were knocked down or trampled late Friday and early today as thousands fled the scene of the gunfight just outside the Cotton Bowl. Police were trying to determine what triggered the violence. The shooting followed a brawl between black and Hispanic fair-goers, said police Cpl. D.H. Boy. Police Sgt. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON> was in stable condition at <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where he underwent surgery, said <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, a nurse at the hospital. The man who police said shot <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON> died of multiple gunshot wounds, Ms. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> said. His name was not released. The incident apparently began around 11:45 p.m. with a shooting in a fair restroom, said police Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>. An officer who overheard the shot chased two or three people through the midway crowd and found the sergeant, the gunman, and another man struggling on the ground, said <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>. A gunbattle ensued between the pursuing officer and the gunman, the captain said. Two other men were shot in addition to the gunman and the sergeant, he said. One was shot in the restroom and the other on the midway. Both were in serious condition, one with a chest wound, the other with a back wound, said a <ORGANIZATION> Parkland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> nurse who declined to give her name. Thousands of people headed for exits when the shooting broke out. Seven pregnant women were treated for injuries or premature labor caused by the fair-goers' stampede. Five other people were trampled or bruised in the crush. <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Pena </PERSON>, 17, said she and a friend tried to climb a six-foot chain link fence to escape the gunfire, but she could not make it because she is seven months pregnant. She and her friend soon were engulfed by the crowd. `` We were both crying and holding each other and did n't know what to do,'' Ms. <PERSON> Pena </PERSON> said while waiting for hospital care. `` Then she fainted.'' <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>, 37, of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, was high above the midway on the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> ferris wheel when the shooting began. `` I heard two or three shots and people in the center _ in the middle _ started running in every direction,'' <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> said. `` After that, you could see people in different spots just running like crazy _ just getting away from this area.''
