<HEAD>Swindall Faces Tough Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> can not tell a jury that charges against him were politically motivated without a hearing that could delay his perjury trial until after the Nov. 8 election, a judge ruled. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> accused <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> of scheming against him for political gain on Friday. He also charged that the government deliberately timed his 10-count indictment shortly before the election. `` They wanted to make darn good and well -LRB- sure -RRB- that they got the indictment before Nov. 8, 1988,'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said of prosecutors. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vining </PERSON>, who began screening potential jurors Friday, ruled that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> may not raise his allegations to the jury without a hearing that could delay his trial until after the election. Barring such a delay, jury selection could be completed and opening arguments in the trial could begin Monday. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> told <PERSON> Vining </PERSON> he would pursue the hearing process `` if it does n't unnecessarily delay the trial,'' but lead prosecutor <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillen </PERSON> immediately served notice he would seek time to prepare a written response to any such move. <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> also said he plans to be on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> next week for legal conferences. <PERSON> Vining </PERSON> said <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> would be free to raise the issue Monday morning. Outside the courtroom, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> declined to comment on his plans. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, a two-term Republican representing the 4th Congressional District of suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, faces Democrat <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> in the election. As he unsuccessfully sought to subpoena <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> to testify at the trial, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> contended it is no accident that he was indicted shortly before the election. He accused <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> _ who, like <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, is a Republican _ of contacting officials in Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s presidential campaign to assess the political impact of his investigation. One of those officials, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, deputy director of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Southern campaign, confirmed he talked with <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> on the day <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was indicted but denied ever having discussed the <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> case with <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> declined comment, citing the pending trial. Later, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said he would subpoena reporters for The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Journal-Constitution and <ORGANIZATION> WSB-TV </ORGANIZATION>, two news organizations which this summer obtained transcripts or videotapes of secretly recorded meetings between <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> and an undercover investigator. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> would not disclose what he wants to ask the reporters on the witness stand, and questioned whether they can legally be compelled to reveal the source of their stories about the recorded conversations. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON>, described by prosecutors as the middleman in the loan negotiations which led to the charges against <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, pleaded guilty to five violations of federal currency laws. LeChasney admitted to charges which do not mention <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, but involve the money-laundering `` sting'' investigation that eventually included a proposed $ 850,000 home mortgage loan for the congressman. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kish </PERSON>, <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON>'s lawyer, said he did no