<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> today welcomed the indictment of <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> racketeering charges, saying it would hasten recovery of the billions of dollars plundered during his 20-year rule. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, in a statement, said she hopes the prosecution in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> of her predecessor will serve as a deterrent to other dictators who steal from their countries and then seek asylum abroad. `` This -LRB- indictment -RRB- is certainly welcome news in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and I commend this evident commitment to the rule of law abroad,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> has been living in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> since he fled the country during the February 1986 civilian-military revolt that swept Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to power. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> invited <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to take up residence in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> claims in a lawsuit filed in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> that he was deceived into leaving the country against his will. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, are restricted to the island of <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION> because of his reported attempt last year to return to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are honoring a <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government request that he not be allowed to return. On Friday, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government indicted former President <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, his wife and eight associates on charges of racketeering. They could face 20-year prison sentences if found guilty. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was the highest-ranking former foreign official indicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The charges alleged that between September 1972, when <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> declared martial law in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, and 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Marcoses </ORGANIZATION> amassed $ 103 million through embezzlement, theft, bribes and kickbacks. According to the indictment, the Marcoses illegally funneled the money through secret bank accounts in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and then used the money to buy valuable <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> properties. `` I hope that this and other similar efforts undertaken in other countries to investigate the crimes of the Marcoses will lead to the early recovery of the stolen assets that rightfully belong to the Filipino people,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s government has accused the Marcoses of stealing up to $ 10 billion in public and private assets during <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' rule. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> formed the five-member <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Good Government to try to recover the wealth and bring the Marcoses to trial. The commission's former chairman, <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trial will save the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> time in efforts to recover assets. `` A lot of evidence that we would have to present before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts -LRB- to recover <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> property -RRB- will already have been presented,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION>, Swiss authorities have ordered records on some Swiss financial transactions made by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, saying those records can be turned over to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Aquino government alleges that