<HEAD>Charge Of Alcohol Use At Atomic Plant Shows Need For NRC Rule,
Lawmaker Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new allegation of alcohol abuse at a nuclear power plant illustrates the need for strict federal regulations to detect substance abuse at atomic reactors, says the chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee. `` It is the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s -RRB- responsibility to protect against drug and alcohol abuse,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> and Insular Affairs subcommittee on investigations and oversight `` It is not enough for the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> to leave it to the industry to regulate itself.'' <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, who has held a series of hearings on the question of substance abuse at nuclear plants, wants the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> to issue stiff regulations on drug and alcohol abuse instead of leaving regulations up to individual utilities. The commission proposed a new rule last month that would require reactor owners to conduct random drug tests, test employees for drugs based on cause, report drug use to the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> and mandate personnel sanctions. But the rule would leave alcohol detection and enforcement up to `` the prudent judgment of each utility.'' Commission officials say no final decision has been made on the proposed regulation. In latest allegation of substance abuse at an atomic reactor, <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> provided The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> with an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> document outlining an accusation made by an employee at the <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> Power Station in <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, against a senior plant manager. The employee, according to the report, told a superior that the manager had alcohol on his breath and stumbled as he passed through a radiation-detecting device on the night of Oct. 10. But officials at <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, operator of the reactor, said the company hired a private investigator the next day who concluded several days later that there was no evidence of alcohol abuse. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, assistant vice president at the plant, defended the utility's internal substance abuse program. In a telephone interview Friday, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said the employee, who was charged with checking for fires at the reactor, reported his accusation to a superior. The shift supervisor talked to the senior manager `` at length'' and decided there was no evidence of alcohol. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said under the company's internal regulations, the manager could have been ordered to take a blood test if the supervisor found cause. He said such blood tests have been ordered in the past. The subsequent investigation turned up no evidence to corroborate the alcohol charge, he said. But <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, who wrote a letter to <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> last week urging a strict rule on both alcohol and drugs, and a top <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> aide said it is wrong to rely on self-policing and criticized the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> for not conducting its own investigation. `` At the very least you want the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> to do is find out what happened,'' said subcommittee investigator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheibel </PERSON>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> ca n't take the trouble to send somebody out there? `` The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> is in a position of public trust, and at the very least the public can expect the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> to act cautiously and not just accept the word of the person who said, ` No, there was no problem','' he said. Commission spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> was `` looking into'' the allegation, but said he did not know to what extent. <PERSON> Scheibel </PERSON> said he was told by <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> officials the agency is not conducting a separate investigation. <PERSON> Scheibel </PERSON> noted that the senior manager in question was a higher ranking official at the company than the shift supervisor who would have had to order the blood test. He said that could be an `` inhibiting factor.'' But plant officials said a thorough _ and independent _ investigation was conducted and that no other employees corroborated the alcohol allegation. The <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> report comes on the heels of a subcommittee hearing earlier this month that focused on an allegation of alcohol abuse against a plant manager at the <ORGANIZATION> Davis-Besse </ORGANIZATION> reactor near <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>.
