<SECOND>AM-Dogs, Bjt,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icelandic Residents Vote On Ruff-erendum On Dog Ownership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AGUST ASGEIRSSON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents of <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION> are getting one last chance to stop the capital from going to the dogs. This week, they vote on an experimental program relaxing a ban on dogs in the city of 88,000. The weeklong referendum begins Monday and asks voters to say whether the 4-year-old program has been a success. City Hall banished dogs in 1924 following an outbreak of dog-related disease. For 60 years it resisted attempts to overturn the ban, despite ridicule from abroad and lurid stories about mass slaughter of illicit dogs. In 1978, dog owners went to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in an unsuccessful bid to have the ban declared unconstitutional. The issue made headlines again when <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gudmundsson </PERSON>, then the finance minister, threatened to emigrate unless he could keep his dog in <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>. Compromise finally came in 1984 when City Hall, while keeping the ban on the books, set up some exemptions and promised a referendum after four years on how <PERSON> Reykavik </PERSON> and man's best friend were getting along. `` We are of the opinion that the vote is not necessary because of the good experience we've had in allowing conditional dog-ownership,'' Mayor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Oddsson </PERSON>, who owns a German shepherd named <PERSON> Tanni </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> -RRB-, recently told <ORGANIZATION> Morgunbladid </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>'s main newspaper. But nevertheless, the promised ballot box is being set up in the city sports hall, and citizens will vote yes or no on the question: `` Do you think that the experimental dog rules have been successful?'' <PERSON> Oddsson </PERSON> said the vote is not binding but if there is an overwhelming majority either way, then `` we must take notice of that.'' With opinion polls showing 2-1 support for the exemptions, dog owners are confident. But one city official, <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON> <PERSON> Oskarsson </PERSON>, said voters are so apathetic on the issue they may ignore the referendum and give anti-dog forces a victory by default. Strict rules apply to <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>'s 850 registered dog owners. Annual licenses cost $ 120, dogs must undergo an annual medical checkup, and owners must have insurance. The city center is permanently out of bounds, and dogs must stay out of public parks between 8 a.m. and 9 p.m. They can not enter public buildings, restaurants, children's playgrounds, barbershops, prisons, cemeteries, morgues and buses. Leashes are always required. According to city veterinarian <PERSON> Oddur </PERSON> <PERSON> Runar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hjartarson </PERSON>, the ban was imposed after dogs began transferring a dangerous sheep disease to human beings. Hyatid disease, which once infected an estimated 20 percent of <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>'s population, is caused by a worm that can cause blindness in people and even death, <PERSON> Hjartarson </PERSON> said. Dogs picked up the disease from eating the intestines of slaughtered sheep. The disease has since been eradicated and illegal dog ownership has become rampant _ along with the lurid stories. `` There were all these stories in the foreign press about dogs being caught and killed. It never happened. I recall perhaps one example of a dog being impounded,'' <PERSON> Oskarsson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gudrun </PERSON> <PERSON> Gudjohnsen </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Dog-Breeding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, warns a new ban `` would be a big step backward'' and not likely to be enforced. `` During the 60 years of the old ban, there were hundreds of dogs in the capital. People ... ought to realize that it is far better to have an effective monitoring and control system than going back to a system of no control,'' she said.
