<HEAD>An Agreement at Last, But Round Two May Be a Killer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The difficulty of reaching a short-term agreement under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> keeps its military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> raises what was once an unthinkable notion _ an eventual <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> pullout from <ORGANIZATION> Subic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Air </PERSON> <PERSON> Base </PERSON>. The agreement signed last week after six months of sometimes-bitter negotiations covers only the use of the bases until 1991, providing for $ 962 million in economic and military aid for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> over the next two years. It is a sharp increase, but many Filipino politicians say it's far from enough. If the Americans are to remain beyond Sept. 30, 1991, the negotiators probably will face difficulties which were only hinted at in this year's talks, according to analysts. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> scholar, said until the talks brought to the fore the spectre of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pullout from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, `` it was sort of an unthinkable, unmentionable issue.'' As the talks were going on, both Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could move its bases if the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> demanded too much. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who is with the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION>, an independently funded think tank, predicted that if nationalist forces continue to shape the debate in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> over the bases, negotiators for both sides will consider a phaseout of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The debate in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> also will be affected by how well the current agreement is implemented. The funds promised in the agreement, while falling short of the annual $ 1.2 billion sought by the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, are still substantially higher than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid appropriated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in previous years for use of the bases. And in light of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget crunch, the difference is significant. Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> minority in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, raised a warning flag: `` Just how that money is going to be found in a foreign operations budget already carved to the bone to meet other base rights and peace-keeping commitments is not readily apparent to this senator.'' But an influential legislative aide who spoke only on condition of anonymity said that there is enough bipartisan support for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> so that `` there are ways the money could be found.'' He conceded this would mean short-changing other aid recipients or wrangling with the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for some of its money. `` It wo n't be easy,'' he said. Another struggle is expected over a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contribution to a $ 5 billion multinational aid program to help ease the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>' $ 28 billion debt. Although the package is unrelated, resolution of the base pact was expected to boost support in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for the international initiative. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is spearheading the effort, although <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will foot most of the bill. The international aid package, if it is approved and funded, `` will grant legitimacy'' to the U.S.-Philippine bases agreement in the eyes of the Filipino public and leadership, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bresnan </PERSON>, a senior research associate at the <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. So far, President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> is facing a hard time selling the new agreement to intellectuals and <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s urban middle class, who accuse her government of selling out their country's sovereignty But some analysts said that if Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> wants the Americans to stay, she must bring the debate before the broad public and take a position herself. `` She has to take a stand and begin to shape opinion,'' said <PERSON> Bresnan </PERSON>. Retired Gen. <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON>, former national security adviser who headed a study of the bases issue for the Council on Foreign Relations in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said, `` What we have to hope for is that the Filipino people weigh in on this, because there is overwhelming support among them for the bases.'' The Filipinos who oppose the continued <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence `` feel that as long as we're there, they ca n't cut the umbilical cord with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON>, `` and nothing we can do will change that.''
