<HEAD>Nationalism And One-Party Rule Hinder Reform in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In dealing a blow to an ambitious Serbian politician, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders have shown how difficult it is to quell ethnic turmoil or introduce democracy in this one-party state. With millions watching on television, the Communist elite last week ended 38 hours of bitter debate with a dramatic rebuff to <ORGANIZATION> Serbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> party leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>. A close ally of <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ckrebic </PERSON>, was the only member of the ruling Politburo not to win a secret vote of confidence Wednesday from the party's policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Ckrebic, an old-time Communist in his 60s, immediately offered his resignation. But <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> angrily intervened to stop consideration of the offer, and <PERSON> Ckrebic </PERSON> remains on the Politburo for now. Another Ckrebic ally charged that an `` unprincipled coalition'' tried to bring <PERSON> Ckrebic </PERSON> down to hurt <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>. The meeting, which did little to tackle the growing economic crisis, gave <PERSON> Yugoslavs </PERSON> a revealing look at their squabbling leadership. Serbs who have rallied round <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s campaign for greater Serbian control over the provinces of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> were furious that only a Serb _ Ckrebic _ fell victim to the unprecedented vote of confidence for Politburo members. `` Did you see what they did to us?'' fumed a <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> television journalist. The next day, 20,000 Serbs in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> protested the outcome. Chanting `` We will not give up Ckrebic!'' they literally turned their backs on two Politburo members who came to address complaints that the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> session did nothing to meet their demands. The 200,000 <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Serbs </LOCATION> and Montenegrins, a minority in what was once a <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> heartland, want to end alleged harassment by the ethnic <PERSON> Albanian </PERSON> majority. They also want to oust some ethnic Albanian Communist leaders. The call for action extends far beyond <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>. With inflation at 217 percent and living standards halved since 1980, most of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s 23 million people are fed up with leaders they perceive as ineffectual and corrupt. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s response to the widespread demand for new leaders was the vote of confidence and the prospect that a third of the committee's 165 members would be replaced in the next six weeks. That would constitute the single biggest sweep of top party ranks since Stalinists were purged after <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s break with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1948. But it fell short of widespread expectations of an immediate shake-up, and the choice of who should fall is likely to get mired in the usual battle among the party leaderships of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics and two provinces. The broad powers given those eight leaderships under the 1974 constitution have enabled widely varying political cultures to develop. The most obvious gap is between the rich, Western-oriented north and the bankrupt, backward southern areas of <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>. Another rift has opened up between liberal northern <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and the demagogic populism of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>. Party chief <PERSON> Stipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Suvar </PERSON>, from the republic of <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, hailed the vote of confidence in Politburo members as a step to party democracy. But the way <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> tried to undo the verdict showed clearly that however much he supports economic and even political reform, he will protect <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s and his own interests first. The leaders agree that change is needed, <PERSON> Suvar </PERSON> said after the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting. But he said the party's only experience in cleaning its own house is in purges ordered from the top. `` We are still learning the rules of the game,'' he said. The half-hearted steps toward political reform show how hard it is for any one-party system to change without the Communists either relinquishing power to some form of popular control or simply carrying out a ruthless purge. <PERSON> Stane </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolanc </PERSON>, a former No. 2 to the late <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, said during the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s debate that the crisis probably cost <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> `` a billion dollars'' in lost foreign investments. <PERSON> Suvar </PERSON> tried to assuage what he said were foreign fears that <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is descending into chaos. `` <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> will not fall apart,'' he said. `` There is a great deal of quarreling in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, but it is not as dangerous as it may appear at first glance.'' But Western creditors are likely to remain uneasy about recovering any of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s $ 21 billion foreign debt. Economic and constitutional reforms designed to attract foreign and private investment are lumbering their way through party and government organs this fall. For years, <LOCATION> Yugoslavs </LOCATION> have called for such reforms _ and more radical ones, such as a return to private farming in this largely agricultural nation. Ironically, the political struggle fueled by the ambitions of <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> may deter foreign investors just as <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> opens up to capitalist investment.
</TEXT>
