re armed to the teeth,'' a senior Lebanese army officer said, also speaking on condition of anonymity. `` They can defend themselves against any Moslem or Syrian attack, but ... they ca n't attack or make any territorial gains.'' The stalemate has sent prices of food, gasoline and other basics soaring. A 2.2-pound can of powdered milk cost 4,000 Lebanese pounds Friday against 2,700 pounds Monday. The Lebanese pound, pegged at 8 to the dollar in 1982 and 337 on Sept. 22, was at 540 Friday. So far, the rival governments have not embarked on an economic war. The Christians easily could cut off electricity, fuel and water supplies to Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. They may be refraining because the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, where 70 percent of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 9.3 million ounces in gold reserves are held, is located on the Moslem side.
