<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TaxBill     10-22 1036</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Bill,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>$4.1 Billion Tax Bill Extends Some Benefits, Adds New Ones</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-The 100th Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the first lessons learned by a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is that there's no better way to keep voters happy than to cut their taxes. There's no money left in the federal treasury to grant any more across-the-board tax reductions such as were approved in 1981. But that does n't prevent the lawmakers from granting targeted relief to one group after another. That's exactly what they did in the tax bill that cleared its final hurdle in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday. It now goes to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and sponsors predict he will sign it. The bill originally was designed to clear up confusing language and correct errors in the landmark tax overhaul enacted in 1986. But it was amended over and over to extend some expiring benefits, add some new ones for selected groups, and raise taxes to finance the benefits. The measure would have no effect on the federal deficit. Although it would cut taxes by $ 4.1 billion over three years, it would raise others by the same amount. And it is not just tax cuts and increases that were attached to the bill. It includes a `` taxpayer's bill of rights'' to rein in what some lawmakers view as an overly aggressive <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>; for example, the agency would have to give 30 days' notice before seizing bank accounts and other property, and would be prohibited from promoting employees on the basis of how much they collect. Some of the other provisions: _ DIESEL: Wipe out a 1987 requirement that farmers, construction companies and other tax-exempt, off-road users of diesel fuel pay the federal tax of 15.1 cents a gallon and later apply for a refund _ MUTUAL FUNDS: For 1988 and 1989, permit owners of mutual fund shares to deduct certain operating expenses of the fund without regard to a general provision allowing deduction of only miscellaneous expenses that exceed 2 percent of income _ HIGHER EDUCATION: Exempt from taxation interest earned on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings bonds that are redeemed to finance a college or vocational education, starting in 1990 _ TUITION AID: Renew for 1988 an expired law allowing a worker to avoid tax on up to $ 5,250 a year of employer-provided education assistance Graduate education would not qualify. _ HOUSING: Extend through 1989 a tax credit for owners of newly constructed low-income rental housing Also, extend through 1989 and modify a tax exemption for bonds issued by state and local governments to help low-income families buy their first home. _ TOBACCO: Impose a tax of 45 cents per pound on pipe tobacco _ WRITERS: Allow free-lance writers, artists and photographers to deduct work-related expenses even before a project produces income _ ` HEIFER TAX': Permit livestock farmers to deduct expenses of producing livestock before the animals begin generating income, thus repealing what has become known as the `` heifer tax.'' _ ATHLETICS: Allow an 80 percent deduction for contributions to college athletic scholarship funds even when such `` gifts'' guarantee a fan the privilege of buying a game ticket _ RESEARCH: Extend through 1989 a credit for increased spending for research and experimentation _ JOB TRAINING: Extend through 1989 a credit under which the government pays the first year of wages for certain newly hired economically disadvantaged workers _ CONTRACTORS: Further restrict the `` completed-contract'' method of accounting that allows defense contractors and most big construction companies to delay taxes on part of their profits until a project is completed This change will raise $ 1.3 billion. _ CORPORATIONS: Accelerate estimated tax payments from corporations that switch from an annualized method of computation, raising $ 869 million _ <LOCATION> ALASKA </LOCATION> CORPORATIONS: Repeal a provision that has allowed <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Native </ORGANIZATION> corporations to sell some of their unused tax credits to other companies; repeal will cost the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> companies $ 1 billion _ LIFE INSURANCE: Remove some of the tax advantages of using single-premium life insurance as an investment Loans from such policies would be taxed as cash withdrawals; the new rules would apply to policies whose cash value builds more quickly than one paid through seven equal annual premiums. The change would cost policyholders $ 345 million. _ MAIL CARRIERS: Allow rural mail carriers to deduct 33.75 cents for each mile a personal car is driven on a mail route; most people are allowed 22.5 cents a mile for business-related mileage _ BUSINESS MEALS: Permit operators of offshore or <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil rigs and of some commercial vessels -LRB- but not luxury liners -RRB- to deduct the full cost of meals provided to employees; most business may deduct only 80 percent _ HOME SALE: Allow a surviving spouse to defer taxation on profits from the sale of a principal home, just as though the spouse had not died Present law denies such a break if a spouse dies after a home is sold and before a new one is built. Also, the provision allowing a person over 55 to avoid tax on up to $ 125,000 of profits from the sale of a principal home in which he or she had lived at least three of the last five years would be available to a person who spends up to four of those five years in a nursing home. _ HOME PHONE: Prohibit any person with a home-based business from deducting any part of the base monthly telephone charge as a business expense _ FARM MACHINERY: Tighten depreciation provisions for single-purpose farm structures, such as poultry houses, and farm machinery _ FARM INCOME: Expand a law allowing farmers to defer for one year income from the drought-forced sale of livestock Also, the measure would ensure that farmers may defer taxes on payments received as a result of drought-caused crop losses. _ BANKS: Renew a tax break for healthy savings and loan associations that take over failing associations, and extend the benefit to banks _ HIGH-SPEED RAIL: Permit use of tax-exempt bonds to finance certain high-speed rail facilities _ BLOOD DONORS: Permit states and blood-collection facilities to require blood donors to list their Social Security numbers so they can be traced if tests determine their blood is carrying the AIDS virus _ AMISH: Exempt from Social Security taxes employees from <LOCATION> Amish </LOCATION> and other sects with religious objections to the program; self-employed Amish already are exempt
