<FIRST>r a AM-Opera     10-22 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Opera,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Forges Final Link In `Ring Cycle' Chain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire and flood consumed the stage of the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in the final scene of <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s `` Goetterdaemmerung,'' but instead of fleeing in panic, the audience leapt to its feet and cheered The triumphant premiere of the new production Friday night meant that the nation's leading opera house had forged the final link in its long-awaited new production of <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s epic `` Ring Cycle.'' The sets and the lighting were among the most spectacular ever seen at the Met and, at least as far as the heroine and the villain were concerned, it seemed as if the company had even brought back the much-lamented bygone Golden Era of Wagnerian singing. Soprano <PERSON> Hildegard </PERSON> <PERSON> Behrens </PERSON>, singing and acting with passion and elegance as the noble <PERSON> Bruennhilde </PERSON>, consolidated her claim as a worthy successor to the great <PERSON> Birgit </PERSON> <PERSON> Nilsson </PERSON>. She and bass <PERSON> Matti </PERSON> <PERSON> Salminen </PERSON> as the baleful <PERSON> Hagen </PERSON> dominated the stage and easily penetrated even the cruelest waves of sound that <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> _ and the Met orchestra _ could provide. Not for 13 seasons had the company performed this last and longest -LRB- nearly six hours including two intermissions -RRB- of the four operas in which <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> intertwined Norse mythology and 19th century German philosophy with sometimes muddled, but generally powerful, results. `` Twilight of the Gods'' as the opera is called in English, turns on <PERSON> Hagen </PERSON>'s determination to get his hands on the magical gold ring that has been the source of all the trouble since his father, <PERSON> Alberich </PERSON>, stole it from the <ORGANIZATION> Rhinemaidens </ORGANIZATION> in the first opera, `` Das Rheingold.'' The plot twists might seem silly were they not redeemed by <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s glorious music, which carries the audience through contrivances like an amnesia-inducing potion and a magical helmet that disguises <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON> so <PERSON> Bruennhilde </PERSON> ca n't recognize her own husband when he kidnaps her. The sets by <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider-Siemssen </PERSON> have combined naturalism with high-tech effects throughout the earlier operas and reach their artistic peak in Act 3. The first scene, a forest clearing where <PERSON> Hagen </PERSON> murders <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON>, is strikingly realistic, the tableau resembling a Flemish painting. <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Wechsler </PERSON>'s lighting moves subtly from dappled sunlight to encroaching darkness as the hero's doom approaches. But the real stage wizardry is saved for the finale, when <PERSON> Bruennhilde </PERSON>'s suicide in <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON>'s funeral pyre literally sets the world ablaze, causes the Rhine to overflow, and even burns up <LOCATION> Valhalla </LOCATION>, the kingdom of the Gods. All this is vividly brought to life as the orchestra, splendidly conducted by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, pours out the final measures of the score. In a performance so strong it's a shame the biggest weakness was the Siegfried of <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>. He seemed ill at ease on stage, his medium-sized voice showed severe strain by Act 2, and he gave only a workmanlike rendition of his wonderful final narrative. Baritone <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Raffell </PERSON> failed to make much impression in the thankless role of <PERSON> Gunther </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hagen </PERSON>'s half-brother. Soprano <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Harries </PERSON> did better as <PERSON> Gunther </PERSON>'s sister, <LOCATION> Gutrune </LOCATION>, but had trouble with her high notes. In the small but vital role of <LOCATION> Waltraute </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bruennhilde </PERSON>'s sister, mezzo <PERSON> Christa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> _ who was singing in Ring Cycles 20 years ago _ made a dazzling impression and provided a valuable link with a tradition the Met is bidding to revive. `` Goetterdaemmerung'' will be performed several more times this fall. In the spring, the Met will stage three complete Rings _ one of them on successive Saturday afternoons in April for a nationwide radio audience.
