<HEAD>Meat And Bread Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia-Future, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Meat prices rose Saturday and bread prices will rise by 60 percent, the government said, two days after an unpopular austerity program was amended to allow salary raises for some workers. The <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ekspres </ORGANIZATION> said the latest price increases `` will drive the remaining shoppers out of meat markets'' and will further depress living standards. Thousands of Yugoslavs in recent weeks have protested rising prices in a growing economic crisis in the communist nation. As of Saturday, prime quality steak cost $ 6.36 a pound in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, up from $ 5.55. Ground meat rose from $ 2.21 to $ 3.39 a pound. The cheapest type of bread, now available for 5 cents a pound, will cost 8 cents when new bread prices take effect Sunday, <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ekspres </ORGANIZATION> said. Statistics published here say living standards have dropped to the level of the mid-1960s. Inflation is running as high as 217 percent. Meat prices were boosted considerably three weeks ago. Last year, the government had to cancel sharp increases in bread prices after widespread protests. The average monthly income in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is $ 100, and experts say about 80 percent of it goes for food. Faced with increasing strikes and worker protests, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday eased an austerity program of wage cuts and price rises introduced in May. The amendments allow wages increases of 140 percent to 152 percent this year, but only for workers in profitable companies and in hard-pressed social services like health and education. Another <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> Vecernje </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Novosti </ORGANIZATION>, said about half of Yugoslav companies, employing more than 2 million workers, will not be able to increase their wages because they are not making profits.
