<HEAD>Hurricane Joan Hits Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Killing 7</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with storm downgraded to tropical storm
with 70 mph winds, noon EDT position, death toll at 7. No pickup.
^By BRYNA BRENNAN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> slammed into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> today with 125 mph winds and blinding rain, killing at least seven people and forcing thousands on the region's <LOCATION> Carribean </LOCATION> coast to flee inland The hurricane's winds later dropped to 70 mph, and it was downgraded to a tropical storm, but forecasters predicted heavy rains from the storm would cause flash floods and mud slides in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. Nicaraguan radio reported three dead and dozens injured on <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Corn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, about 45 miles off the city of <LOCATION> Bluefields </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rican </LOCATION> authorities said four drowned and seven were missing there. More than 77,000 people were evacuated in the two countries, authorities said. On <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s coast, the storm flattened homes, felled trees and cut communications. About 1,000 people were evacuated in the early morning darkness after flood waters threatened to engulf a neighborhood in <LOCATION> Bluefields </LOCATION>, 180 miles east of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. The group was taken to a municipal building to ride out the storm, the state radio, Voice of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, reported. Precautionary evacuations also began in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> as the storm swept inland, according to a newspaper report. Severe flooding also was reported in coastal Costa Rican towns, officials there said. <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> has never been hit by a hurricane in recorded history, and the last one that hit <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> was in 1911. Earlier this week, the storm left at least 26 people dead and tens of thousands homeless in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. Forecasters with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said the storm, traveling west at 8 mph, weakened as it passed over land. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> struck <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Corn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> late Friday, state radio reported. Heavy winds and rain knocked out power in <LOCATION> Rama </LOCATION>, 60 miles west of <LOCATION> Bluefields </LOCATION>, and strong downpours were reported in central Chontales and southern <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> provinces. Flash flood and mud slide warnings were issued for <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, western <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. Forecasters predicted more than 15 inches of rain would inundate those areas by Sunday. Storm surges of 10 to 15 feet were expected near and just to the north of the hurricane's center. At noon EDT today, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>'s center was near latitude 11.9 north and longitude 84.5 west, or 120 miles east of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. Maximum sustained winds were 70 mph. `` The danger is effective and real. There exists a great danger of loss of life in the city of <LOCATION> Bluefields </LOCATION>,'' Information Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinoza </PERSON> said Friday night. Neighborhood civil defense committees in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> stacked sandbags to form levees against flooding. Heavy winds and rain prompted the government to evacuate hospitals in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cabezas </LOCATION>, 120 miles north of <LOCATION> Bluefields </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Boaco </LOCATION>, an inland city 45 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. Under an emergency law declared Thursday, the government ordered private firms to make available stocks of goods necessary to confront the hurricane. <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aragon </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Juigalpa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, 100 miles west of the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast, said refugees were streaming into the city ahead of the storm. `` They're carrying everything they can _ chickens, pigs, sacks of beans and other small belongings,'' he said. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> rivers near the Nicaraguan border spilled their banks, as did the <LOCATION> Coto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> side, officials said. Costa Rican officials feared <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> could destroy many of the 20,000 banana plantations along the coast.
