<HEAD>Quayle: ``One-Liners Say a Lot''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, removing extraneous material</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` One-liners say a lot,'' says <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, contending that voters have been well informed this year even though the presidential campaigns have often aimed merely for catchy television `` sound bites.'' `` There are a lot of subtleties communicated with a sound bite,'' the brief TV clip on the evening news, he said. `` People receive messages.'' Voters, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, can receive a complex message from a simple one-liner, especially when such elements as body language are added in. While <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said television coverage of the campaign, the dominant medium for most Americans, has occasionally lacked substance, he also said `` the information is out there'' for voters to make up their minds. Both of the presidential compaigns spend millions of dollars on television advertising, and they arrange candidate appearances and speeches with an eye toward getting a particular few seconds on the news. But <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said that is n't all bad. `` What you have right now is you have to get a story across and the temptation is to say ` OK, we've got a message today we want to get across on our own terms and nobody else's,''' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` That's a pretty good strategy,'' he said. `` You ca n't fault the strategy.'' `` The people, by and large, know a lot about all four of us,'' he said. `` It's more oriented to one-liners, but, you know, one-liners say a lot. `` Let's not minimize the importance of one-liners.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> made his comments Friday night in an interview as his campaign plane returned to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after he spent a week stumping in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and South. In the interview, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was mildly critical of the coverage of the campaign but generally satisfied that voters had been told what they need in order to make a choice. `` I found out that, at least in my own case, sometimes I've given what I think have been very susbtantative speeches ... There does n't seem to be much interest in covering it,'' he said. `` The question is, have we been well-served? I think we know a lot about <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bsh </PERSON>. I think they really have a very good idea of the four candidates.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he's now more comfortable as a national candidate because `` a national campaign is now something that's more behind me than ahead of me.'' That comfort level is increased because he's now settling into the traditional role of a vice presidential candidate rather than a lightning rod for controversy, he said. That point was underscored, he said, by a telephone call he received from his wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, late in the week. `` She said ` you must really be giving great speeches, having great crowds, doing all the right things, because I have n't heard a thing about you out here,''' he said. `` Welcome to the traditional role of the vice presidential campaign.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said both of the presidential campaigns have dealt with substantative issues. `` There have been a number of speeches, a number of debates, probably too many speeches,'' he said. `` The information is out there. The question is on how this information gets communicated. `` The question then becomes, what is being communicated? Is it the 15-second sound bite? `` I'll be interested to find out what we've learned from this,'' he said. `` I think we've got to rethink it on both sides. `` You have to look at how television is used by both campaigns,'' he said. `` It is very difficult to do in a substantative way, even though there have been substantative speeches. `` I'm sure we'll go back and there'll be new benchmarks, there'll be new standards, maybe some old standards will be thrown away.''
