<HEAD>Lawyers See Two Sides To Congressman's Hurry-up Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> is attempting to beat an Election Day deadline with his one-man, rush-to-justice defense in a federal perjury trial that will climax one of the country's most bitter congressional elections. If everything goes as expected, the two-term <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman will deliver his opening argument in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, just one week after his indictment was handed up and just 15 days before the Nov. 8 election. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, a lawyer, is representing himself in the perjury case and hopes a quick acquittal will bring victory at the polls. He has admitted to a mistake in judgment in negotiating an $ 850,000 loan last year with an undercover agent posing as a financier, but denies criminal wrongdoing. Eventually, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> accepted a $ 150,000 check from a middleman, then returned it uncashed. The 10 perjury charges brought against <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> stem from his testimony before a grand jury in February. Among other things, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> testified he could not recall any mention of drug money; tapes of the meetings have the agent saying the loan money was probably drug-related. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> is facing the same challenger he did in 1986 in his bid for a third term in the House. He calls it a race between `` a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> liberal and a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> conservative.'' Voters in the suburbs east of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> will choose between <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a one-time `` Dukes of Hazzard'' TV star who has had to answer repeated questions from <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> about his admitted bout with alcoholism. Though <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> demanded the speedy trial to obtain a verdict before the election, he has stressed his disadvantage in manpower and time to prepare for the trial, saying he will just have to rely on the `` ol' innocent defense.'' In fact, he will have more going for him, said lawyer <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a former policeman and prosecutor who was the Republican nominee for governor in 1986. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> has been a critic of <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> but expressed admiration for his tactics in the case. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said he has seen both laymen and lawyers successfully defend themselves. `` Many defendants found that there was an advantage in that the jury was continously being exposed to the defendant himself while he conducts the trial,'' he said. If <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> is a good courtroom performer, he said, he will be able to impress his case on the jurors `` from the time the trial starts, and not just from the time he takes the witness stand.'' But <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fierer </PERSON>, who has handled a string of high-profile criminal cases and represents another defendant in the money-laundering probe, said that while <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> may get the underdog's sympathy from the jury, he is sacrificing some potentially important options in rushing to trial. `` He really has given up investigative time, the time to go out and find witnesses, to get prepared on witnesses, and that sort of thing,'' Fierer said. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, however, noted that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> has had access to transcripts of his meetings with the undercover agent for some time, `` so he's probably, no doubt, well-prepared to go to trial. And I think probably it is a wise thing for him to do.'' And <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said some pre-trial skirmishing over what can be used in court and demands for information are not as crucial to <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> because `` in this case, the facts are fairly simple.'' If the trial starts Monday, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> also gives up time for pre-trial hearings that could have helped his defense, especially on his claims that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, also a Republican, is promoting his career at <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>'s expense. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vining </PERSON> ruled that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> may not present those claims to the jury without conducting a pre-trial hearing on whether <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> could be subpoenaed. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> has n't officially told the judge whether he wants the hearing, but he has indicated he will not permit a delay in the trial It will be up to the jury to decide whether <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> can reconcile the tapes of his meetings with the undercover agent with his later grand jury testimony. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> has vowed to show his answers were not deceitful because he simply could not remember everything said in the negotiations. The 38-year-old congressman has had to curtail campaigning, saying the trial has become the campaign's most important factor. His pre-indictment polls, he said, found a dead heat. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' campaign manager, <PERSON> Maren </PERSON> <PERSON> Hesla </PERSON>, disagreed `` Congressman <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> has attempted to make the verdict the election, but that's just not the case,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hesla </PERSON> said. `` We enjoyed an 18-point lead prior to the indictment.'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who has acknowledged a conviction for assault on his wife during the days he was battling alcoholism, has been quiet about his opponent's criminal case. Ms. <PERSON> Hesla </PERSON> acknowledged that <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> has lost news media attention because of the focus on <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>'s case. `` We're doing what we can to be out there meeting the voters right now,'' she said.
