<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s weekly radio address Saturday, from <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>: In less than three weeks, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people will elect a new president. It may be the most important election of this century. On the surface, this election has been a series of negative TV ads, quicky polls and instant experts. The ads, the polls, and the experts seem to be driving the process. Most Americans are unhappy with what they are seeing on their televisions. We are a big people and we want a wide view of what's at stake in this election Everything important to the American people can not be reduced to a seven-second sound bite. The ads on television are n't going to tell you much of anything. A little music, some flag waving, and then `` poof'' the ad is over. It's time to look beneath the surface and start asking the important questions. We need a president who tends to the nation's business; who has a sense of the future. We need a president who has a plan for making the trade deficit a trade surplus; who is willing to make a real commitment to ending the policy of borrow and debt that has put us into a sea of red ink. We need a president who wants to keep <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> strong and who knows that economic power and military strength go hand in hand. We need a president who believes in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> so much that he is not afraid to tell us we have problems that need fixing. We need a president who ways the same thing in public that he says in private and who wo n't make secret deals with the Ayatollah. Two years ago, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people put the Democrats back in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. We won in 1986 because we told the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people we would make a difference in their lives. Our agenda was clear and exact: check and balance a White House that seemed to have lost its way. We delivered despite two years of confrontation. When the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people asked for a clean water bill, we delivered despite a White House that said no. When American workers wanted a new trade bill and jobs for Americans, we delivered despite a White House that said no. When the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people demanded fairness on plant closing, we delivered despite a White House that said no. When the American people demanded an end to the `` slash and burn'' education policy of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, it was the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that said yes. So who is in the mainstream of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> politics? A look at the record of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will answer that question. This <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has tried to be a `` family'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. We have tackled the problems that people talk about when they sit around the kitchen table. For our senior citizens, we have expanded <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> to include catastrophic health insurance. For two-paycheck families, we fought for parental leave and child care bills, only to run into a White House filibuster. For millions of working men and women, we fought for an increase in the minimum wage despite White House opposition. For our nation's security, we fought against waste and fraud in the Pentagon. As majority leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats, I take pride in the work of the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. We have done our duty. We have addressed your concerns. We have listened to the people. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> once said that `` polls are like sleeping pills designed to lull voters into sleeping on election day.'' Do n't let the polls lull you to sleep. Do n't let the political hucksters pick the next president. Look beneath the surface. Look to the record. Vote for the future. Remember that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is always at its best when we face our problems and never stand still. Thank you and God Bless You.
