<HEAD>Key Events in Attempts to Free Whales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a chronology of major events in the attempts to free the three trapped whales in <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>: Oct. 13 _ The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> gray whales were discovered trapped in the ice east of <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION>. They apparently became stuck a week before. Biologists were unable to contact an icebreaker to give aid. Oct. 14 _ The whales continued to swim several hundred feet offshore, using two holes in the ice to breathe. Biologists believed time was running out for the grays as nighttime temperatures dropped to 13 degrees below zero, threatening to shrink the whales' breathing space. Efforts failed again to contact an icebreaking ship. Oct. 18 _ A biologist said one whale may have pneumonia, as an <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Skycrane </ORGANIZATION> helicopter went to tow a 185-ton Hovercraft-type icebreaking barge 200 miles northwest to the whales. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> telephoned with his support. Oct. 19 _ <ORGANIZATION> Eskimos </ORGANIZATION> cut new holes in ice, but the barge effort was hampered by shallow water. Biologists said the whales' health appeared to be stabilized, and that they were handling their captivity better than first believed. Oct. 20 _ The barge began its journey but moved only about six miles through sand bars, mud and shallow water. Two <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> brothers-in-law arrive with de-icers to enlarge breathing holes for whales. Oct. 21 _ One of the whales, nicknamed `` Bone,'' disappeared and was presumed dead. Rescuers tried `` Plan B:'' A five-ton concrete `` bullet'' wielded by a helicopter loaned by the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. Easterly wind opened `` leads,'' or open water, through the ice within four miles of the whales. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> offered an icebreaker to help in the rescue. Oct. 22 _ Eskimos using chain saws had led the whales almost a half-mile closer to open water by carving a string of 24 breathing holes in the ice. The Skycrane dropping its `` bullet'' had punched four 15-to-20-foot holes in the ice at 75-yard intervals, but a massive pressure ridge of ice stood in the way.
