<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Police Stations; Opposition Criticizes New
Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas attacked two small police stations in the south with machine guns and anti-tank rockets, killing a corporal and wounding a local farmer, police said Saturday. They were the first significant terrorist actions since right-wing President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> lost an Oct. 5 referendum on extending his rule to 1997. According to a national police statement, eight guerrillas opened fire Friday night with machine guns and M-16 rifles on a small frontier post in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quenes </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> Andes </LOCATION> foothills 20 miles east of the city of <LOCATION> Curico </LOCATION>. The guerrillas then set a police building afire, destroying it and a police jeep, the statement said. It said the gunfire killed a corporal, <PERSON> Juvenal </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON>, and wounded a farmer visiting the post, <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>. An hour earlier, other guerrillas fired two anti-tank rockets at another police post in <LOCATION> Pichipellahuen </LOCATION>, 55 miles southwest of the town of <LOCATION> Traiguen </LOCATION>, the communique said. There were no injuries reported in the attack. The communique blamed both attacks on the communist <ORGANIZATION> Manuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rodriguez </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. A spokeswoman for a dissident faction of the front called foreign news agencies in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> to claim responsibility for the actions, saying they represented the start of a `` national patriotic war.'' Interior Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON> called the police officer's death `` an extremely cold terrorist act'' and called on Chileans `` to understand that this country wants to achieve democracy on a peaceful level. <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON> was named Friday, when <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> replaced half of his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>'s 16 members in a shake-up prompted by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s 800,000-ballot loss in his bid to extend his term The 72-year-old army commander seized power in a 1973 coup. Under the constitution, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remains in power until March 1990. The winner of open elections planned for December 1989 will take over. While swearing in his new ministers, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> firmly rejected opposition calls to step down early and for consitutional reforms. Opposition leaders said his declaration and new Cabinet choices dashed their hopes for prompt negotiations on the reforms. ` The Cabinet is the same, only the names are different,'' said <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON>, vice-president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest. `` It does n't ... reflect the feeling of the immense majority of Chileans who voted ` no' on Oct. 5.'' <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON>, however, called on the opposition's ranks to `` keep a cool head and firm nerves'' and not to resort to violent actions. The coalition has repeatedly condemned leftist terrorist actions, saying they provide an excuse for government repression. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, a prominent Socialist, noted that two army generals, Public Works Minister <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Siebert </PERSON> and Economy Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Concha </PERSON>, and a retired navy admiral, Defense Minister <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Carvajal </PERSON>, were retained while generals from the air force and national police were ousted. The air force and national police are considered more politically moderate than the navy or <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s fiercely loyal army.
