<HEAD>Former Minnesota Rabbi David Aronson Dies At Age 96</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rabbi <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Rabbinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, has died after a short illness. He was 96. `` He was one of the leading rabbis, nationally, in the last 60 years,'' said <PERSON> Rabbi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kassel </PERSON> <PERSON> Abelson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>'s successor at <LOCATION> Beth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Synagogue </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. `` His work was very important, especially where it concerned Jewish annulments and divorces,'' <PERSON> Abelson </PERSON> said. `` His book, ` The Jewish Way of Life,' published in 1945, has become a classic and has been reprinted many times.'' <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> in 1892 and grew up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He attended <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the Jewish Theological Seminary in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. After ordination in 1919, <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON> served congregations in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, before joining <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> El </PERSON> in 1924. From 1948 to 1950, he was president of the <ORGANIZATION> Rabbinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, an assembly of 1,200 Conservative rabbis. <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>, who died Thursday, is survived b