<HEAD>Million-Dollar Reward Offered For Identity Of Secret Client _ If</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Relatives of a man who was killed in an unsolved hit-and-run are offering as much as $ 1 million to anyone with information leading to the driver's identity. But the family says that before it can pay off, it first must win a $ 6 million lawsuit against the driver, and his identity apparently is known only to one person, an attorney who has won court permission to keep it secret because of lawyer-client privilege. That lawsuit is pending in <ORGANIZATION> Palm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, while state and private investigators continue trying to track down the driver of the car. The suit was filed in February over the March 9, 1986, crash that killed <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Baltes </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. Attorney <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Krischer </PERSON> says the driver approached him for counsel the day after the accident and he has steadfastly refused to publicly identify him. On Oct. 12, Circuit Judge <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Poulton </PERSON> said <PERSON> Krischer </PERSON> did not have to reveal that information because it is protected by attorney-client confidentiality. `` This criminal is out there laughing at the system, hiding behind the attorney-client privilege,'' says <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Farish </PERSON>, attorney for <PERSON> Baltes </PERSON>' family. He devised the reward plan, announced Friday, `` in order to make incentive for someone to come forward and expedite this mystery.'' <PERSON> Farish </PERSON> conceded that if someone comes forward with information leading to the driver's identity, the tipster would have to wait for a favorable jury verdict in the lawsuit. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubin </PERSON>, who represents <PERSON> Krischer </PERSON>, said he is indifferent to <PERSON> Farish </PERSON>'s tactics, as long as <PERSON> Farish </PERSON> does not trample on the judge's ruling. `` It's really not my concern as long as he and everyone else respects the attorney-client privilege,'' <PERSON> Lubin </PERSON> said. `` Anything that Mr. <PERSON> Farish </PERSON> or the <PERSON> Baltes </PERSON> family will do to help us is welcome,'' said Chief Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Selvig </PERSON>. `` If this helps, we welcome it.''
