<HEAD>American-Israel Lobby Group Called Most Powerful on Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 18-19 pvs, bgng: ``The memo ...'' to CORRECT
spelling of Chafee.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A rare, public rift in the Jewish community, controversy over a political memo and harsh words from <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> have focused attention on <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>, one of the most powerful lobbying groups on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, referred to as <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>, is well-known in the corridors of power even though its staff generally stays out of the limelight and prefers to work behind the scenes. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dine </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director, rarely gives interviews, and <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> officials are not regulars on the television and radio talk show circuit. Yet <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> has compiled a stunningly successful record since 1951 in promoting the relationship between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> is the largest recipient of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic and military aid, amounting to $ 3 billion this year. `` It's the strongest lobby in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the strongest lobby in the country,'' said former Rep. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Findley </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> who wrote a book attacking <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> after his defeat in 1982. `` It remains a powerhouse on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> because they have an excellent, highly professional, highly trained staff,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> staff members track legislation and have broad contacts at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and in the White House. <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> and its allies in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have played a large role in opposing the sale of weapons to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, in a speech to an Arab-American group Friday, said congressional opposition to the sale of weapons to moderate Arab countries was costing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` tens of billions of dollars worth of jobs.'' <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, upset that its attempts to buy weapons such as new fighter jets and Maverick antitank missiles from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> often have been stymied by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, recently signed a deal with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to buy more than $ 30 billion worth of weapons. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> did not mention <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> by name, but he criticized `` various interest groups and many in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>'' for trying to block sales to Arab countries. `` The notion that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense cooperation with moderate <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states poses a danger to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is ill-founded and untrue,'' he said. But Rep. <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, D-Calif., a strong backer of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, said, `` Such sales are not in the American interest of peace in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Findley </PERSON>, in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said he thinks <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s real power stems from an indirect linkage between the lobby and pro-Israel political action committees controlled by Jewish groups. <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> strenuously denies the allegation and says it does not make political contributions or endorse candidates. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Dershowitz </PERSON> reiterated this position in a letter to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Jewish Week, which had published a story saying the <ORGANIZATION> CBS-TV </ORGANIZATION> show `` 60 Minutes'' was looking into the relationship between <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> and pro-Israel political action committees. `` ` 60 Minutes' has no new ` evidence' that <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> coordinates or directs PACs,'' she said, adding that earlier allegations fall `` far short of ` proving' any such direction or coordination.'' <PERSON> Dershowitz </PERSON> also disavowed a 1987 memo written by a former junior staffer at the lobbying group to another ex-staffer, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Amouyal </PERSON>. The memo discussed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, describing <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> incumbent <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON> as a `` poor supporter of our issue.'' It called for encouragement of the candidacy of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Licht </PERSON>, the state's lieutenant governor who is Jewish. `` No such negative campaign exists'' against <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dershowitz </PERSON> said. While <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> always has been a magnet for criticism from some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the airing of a disagreement in the Jewish community over the lobby's activities was unusual. Six officials of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZA