<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0645 to delete extraneous paragraph.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stage has been set for a complex land swap involving the 111-acre <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> campus and more than 100,000 acres of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> swampland. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation concerning the swap on Thursday. The bill authorizes the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to dispose of the school, which the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration wants to close because of declining enrollments. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative wing of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, has described the downtown <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> land as perhaps the most valuable undeveloped piece of urban real estate in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. Under the plan, the <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> family interests of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> will get 68.4 acres of the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> property in exchange for the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> acreage and a cash payment of at least $ 34.9 million. The transaction also calls for the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to get 11.5 acres of the school property to expand its <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> hospital; <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> to get 20 acres for a park; and <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> to get 4.5 acres for a veterans home. The rest of the land is tied up in road rights-of-way. The money paid by the <ORGANIZATION> Colliers </ORGANIZATION> will be placed into a trust fund for the education of Indians in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> land will be used to provide a buffer around the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> and to provide habitat for endangered species, such as the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> panther. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 316-32 approval of a package of bills in which the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> deal was included. The measure was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> a week ago, but was approved again by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> later Thursday and sent to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for his signature. The new <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote was necessitated by a minor change made by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>.
