<HEAD>Father Charged With Slashing Two Young Sons Throats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Puffe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, separated from his wife, wanted to be with his two little boys. Now, he sits in an isolated jail cell with a wound healing on his neck. He slashed his throat and lived. Police say he slashed the throats of <PERSON> Timmy </PERSON>, 3, and <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON>, 2. They were buried Saturday. The 29-year-old father was charged last week with two counts of first-degree murder, but a judge granted him permission Thursday to see the boys one final time before their funerals. <PERSON> Puffe </PERSON> and his 27-year-old wife, <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON>, were getting a divorce and custody of the boys was going to be a major issue. She and the children had moved out in August and a temporary court order let <PERSON> Puffe </PERSON> have the children on Sundays. <PERSON> Puffe </PERSON> was being held in lieu of $ 500,000 cash bail in a cell equipped with a television monitor where officers `` are watching him a bit more closely'' than other inmates, said Chief Deputy <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Andraschko </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Waupaca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> will not have died in vain if we would see children as a gift from God and not pawns in the lives and desires of adults,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Gauerke </PERSON> told about 100 mourners Saturday at <ORGANIZATION> Trinity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. The church pastor urged family and friends to reflect on the `` joy and unending enthusiasm and vitality'' of the boys and to forgive their father. The killings Oct. 15 left people stunned in the neighborhood of neat lawns, no fences and well-kept, ranch-style homes. Basketball hoops, bicyc