<HEAD>Sweeping Anti-Drug Bill Toughens Penalties for Drug Dealing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To update with Moynihan on bill signing, inserts new graf 6:
Sen. Daniel ....</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is expected to sign a broad ranging anti-drug bill that calls for stiff penalties for drug dealers including the death sentence in some cases involving drug-related murders. The bill, characterized by Sen. Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., as `` bad news for drug dealers and their customers,'' was approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> early Saturday `` This is a very strong bill. The message is simple. Do n't do drugs. The country will not tolerate it,'' declared <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. The bill calls for creation of a Cabinet-level `` drug czar'' that would coordinate all aspects of the federal government's war against illegal drugs. It also calls for stiffer penalties and a variety of other sanctions, including loss of some federal benefits and civil fines, for drug violations. White House spokeswoman <PERSON> Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said she did not know when the president will sign the legislation, adding that the bill had not yet been sent over to the White House. Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, one of the principle sponsors of the legislation, said Saturday he expects <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to sign the bill swiftly. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> worked late into the night to enact the legislation that many congressmen and senators wanted in time for the final days of their re-election campaigns. A dispute over proposed anti-obscenity language _ sought by conservatives, but labeled unconstitutional by many liberals and moderates _ held up the vote until the early morning hours Saturday. The matter was worked out when it was agreed to create a new obscenity trafficking offense and the House went on to approve the overall legislation on a 346-11 vote. Two hours later the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed the measure with a voice vote. The bill would allow up to a $ 10,000 civil fine for possession of even small quantities of drugs intended for personal use and could, beginning in September, lead to the loss of student loans and other federal benefits for anyone convicted of drug possession. Drug kingpins and others who kill or order killings while committing drug-related felonies could be executed under a federal death penalty provision in the legislation. Other provisions of the bill would: _ Require for the first time health warning labels on alcoholic beverages _ Toughen child pornography laws, including creation of penalties for anyone who aids in the use of a child for producing sexually explicit materials _ Establishes a one-year pilot program for drug testing of new drivers' license applicants _ Expands the government's role in drug treatment, prevention and research programs _ Allows the president to impose sanctions against countries involved in laundering drug money Because of continuing disagreements among some legislators, provisions that would have required random drug testing for transportation workers and those with safety-related jobs at nuclear facilities were left out of the legislation. In <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Micky </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadoff </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Mothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drunk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Driving </ORGANIZATION>, called the legislation `` a fantastic success'' because of its provisions involving alcohol.
