<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 535 men and women who made up the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had a very good two years or a very bad two years, depending on your point of view. In the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subways did not run on time and senators missed votes, a shouting congressman had his mike turned off, a senator was arrested and <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> stole the show at the Iran-Contra hearings. In the House the telephones stopped working, nearly all of them. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the telephones worked too well, picking up conversations from other offices without the knowledge of those doing the conversing. Six members of the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> ran for their party's presidential nomination _ Reps. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill. None of But two members who did not make the run _ Sens. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ind </LOCATION>., found themselves on their party's ticket anyway, as someone else's vice presidential running <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> was later to contend that the furor over plagiarism that forced him from the race saved his life. Saved his life? <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> spent months in the hospital recovering from operations for a brain aneurysm that was diagnosed shortly after he ended his candidacy. He said, and staff members agreed, that he would have ignored the pain and plunged ahead with his campaign had he not been forced from the race after disclosures he had adopted parts of the speeches of other politicians word for word. That could have killed him, <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 One senator was credited with saving another senator's life. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>. D-Mass., came upon Sen Chic Hecht, R-Nev., in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hallway, choking A slice of apple was stuck in his throat. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, who had never before performed the Heimlich maneuver, applied it four times, successfully dislodging the obstruction. `` He's a strong guy, he picked me right up and knew just what to do,'' said <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>. Any small irony in that? Well, yes. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> is chairman of the Democratic senatorial election campaign, which is doing its best to upset <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>'s bid for re-election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Throughout the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, Democrats struggled to pass a campaign spending limitations bill over Republican opposition. In the end they failed. But the battle will be remembered. At 1:30 a.m. one day last March, Republicans fled the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor to prevent a quorum from being established and to force the Democratic leadership to adjourn. A call went out for the sergeant-at-arms to arrest absent senators. Sergeant-at-Arms <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Giugni </PERSON> used a master key to enter the private office of Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore. <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> was arrested and escorted to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chamber But he refused to enter. <PERSON> Giugni </PERSON> ordered a squad of detectives to lift <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> from his feet and to carry him inside. They did so and his presence gave the Democrats a quorum and the Republicans a severe case of outrage. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> remained in session all night.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> worried about its `` quality of life.'' Younger senators, especially those with children, grumbled about legislative chaos, sessions that stretched deep into the night, roll calls that stretched far beyond their allotted 15 minutes, a `` Tuesday-Thursday Club'' that saw senators stretch a two-day weekend into four. Action was taken. In exchange for time off every fourth week, senators were expected to be present Monday through Friday for the rest of the month. Roll calls were restricted to 15 minutes with no waiting for senators who did not show up on time. Almost immediately the law of unintended consequences went into effect. With the 15-minute clock running, a band of senators piled off elevators in the subway lobby of the <ORGANIZATION> Hart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> building. The roofless, three-car train was waiting. But it was filled with visitors who happened to be blind. It took a while for the senators to get possession of the train. Fuming, they stormed onto the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor minutes after the roll call ended, only to be told that they could not vote and would not be recorded. Now, during roll calls, the trains are reserved for the exclusive transportation of senators.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Senate oratory can get heated, and at times just a little twisted. As the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> neared its end, Sen. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, R-Idaho., complained at length about the failure of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to provide further military aid to the Contras in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> He said: `` The gutless no-good 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on this issue has decided to create its own doctrine, and that is to write it off. `` In other words, we will write off freedom in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, throw them to the alligators and hope the alligators will eat someone else and eat us last and they can peel off a slice of that salami and they will not bother us for now. Do not rock the boat.''
