<HEAD>As Election Nears, Pollsters Still See Uneasy Electorate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 13th graf pvs, bgng: ``An NBC-Journal
...'' to UPDATE with Newsweek poll.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polls are illuminating an electorate in turmoil, with voters still groping _ some of them dispiritedly _ toward a decision in the presidential election, analysts say. While surveys indicate a healthy <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lead, striking differences in gauging the size of the lead underline a certain unhappiness with the choices, some pollsters said in recent days. And that means things still can change with just over two weeks to go, they said. `` People are having lots of second thoughts,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Even in polls that have found stable results for weeks, he said, `` I term it stable uncertainty.'' Several pollsters _ but not all _ agreed with such an analysis: That a good number of voters, even at this late date, remain loosely committed to either <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> or to Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, and could change their minds. `` I see more indecision than usual, and I ascribe that a lot to the negativism of the campaign,'' said I.A. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, chief of polling for the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think there's a kind of reluctance for people to commit themselves to one of two people, neither of whom they like.'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, in the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> poll, has found that four in 10 of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' supporters and nearly three in 10 of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s oppose the other candidate more than they favor their own _ hardly an inspiring reason to cast a vote Gallup has found less than half of each candidate's supporters backing him strongly, and a sizable share, roughly three in 10, saying they could change their minds. And in an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll, 57 percent of likely voters wished they had a different set of choices. `` Neither of these guys seems to attract the kind of commitment that some other presidential candidates have had,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugick </PERSON>, political pollster for Gallup. Even though Gallup has found a stable <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lead since August, he said, `` If you look at the depth of commitment, you'll see there's still potential for change.'' The view of a still-volatile electorate was not unanimous. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON>, pollster for <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, saw a more stable contest. His surveys, like <PERSON> Gallup </PERSON>'s bi-weekly ones, have found a steady lead for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and he has found considerably stronger support for the candidates than Gallup has. `` My polling does n't show very much volatility at all,'' said <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON>, who has polled every night since Labor Day. `` There's a clear indication of a very stable race.'' But not all polls are in line with each other. An <ORGANIZATION> NBC-Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll, taken Friday through Sunday last weekend, found an enormous 17-point <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lead. A Harris poll Friday to Monday the same weekend put it down to nine points. And an <ORGANIZATION> ABC-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll from the previous Wednesday to Tuesday put it at seven, roughly where it's been for weeks. Most recently, a <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> poll of 1,013 registered voters conducted by telephone on Thursday and Friday showed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> leading <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> 50 percent to 41 percent, with a margin of error of 4 percentage points. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> pollster <PERSON> Laurily </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> said her poll could have caught a swing to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> after the presidential debate last week, then missed some shifting back to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on Monday. She noted that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> received wide publicity as the debate winner. Other pollsters shared her view, noting that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> surged after the Democratic convention last summer and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> after the Republican convention, but settled back as the publicity wore off. Their hypothesis: When voters do n't have strong opinions, they are more likely to be influenced by events, albeit momentarily. `` Polling immediately after momentous events catches people in the process of making up their minds. What you see are these distortions,'' said <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON>, the Gallup president. He likened it to a runner's pulse after a race: `` It's an accurate reading. But you ca n't generalize a lot from it.'' <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON> and others said such skittishness in the electorate magnifies the methodological differences in polls _ whether or not they urge undecided voters to make a choice, for example _ and can help skew results.
</TEXT>
