<HEAD>Britain Back To GMT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on Sunday reverted from Summer Time to <ORGANIZATION> Greenwich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>, moving clocks back one hour at 2 a.m. to 1 a.m. <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> did the same. The traditional change again put <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> out of step with most of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which is one hour ahead of GMT in winter and two hours ahead in summer. Summer Time, lasting from March to October, was first introduced in 1916 to provide an extra evening hour of light for farmers and save electricity during World War I. But it also means mornings are darker for an hour.
