<HEAD>Demonstrators Angry over `Sleazy, Cheap' TV Drama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An AIDS support organization Saturday called an <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> series sleazy for an episode depicting the fictitious murder of a bisexual man who knowingly infects sexual partners with the deadly virus. `` NBC should not exploit the human tragedy of the AIDS epidemic to increase rating points and profits,'' said <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfred </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AIDS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. Fearing the episode would unleash violence against carriers of the virus, 60 demonstrators earlier this week shut down the shooting on an outdoor scene of `` Midnight Caller,'' an action drama series set in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The first episode is scheduled to air Tuesday night. The protests, set to resume Monday when <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> productions resumes shooting, began after negotiations between several AIDS groups, the show's producers, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> officials and representatives of the mayor's office failed to reach an agreement on changes in the script. `` We are not asking <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and the producers to cancel a ` Midnight Caller' episode on AIDS,'' <PERSON> Wolfred </PERSON> said in a statement Saturday. `` We would wholeheartedly support an episode that promotes understanding of HIV disease.'' A handout distributed with the statement called the disputed episode, which will be shown sometime in the future, `` sleazy ... sensational ... cheap television drama.'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said it has agreed to talk more with demonstrators next week but insisted shooting will resume on Monday. In the episode in question, a bisexual man carrying the AIDS virus purposely infects others by having sexual relations with them. One of the partners, a woman who discovers she carries the AIDS virus, shoots and kills the man at the end of the episode. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, executive producer of the program, said he decided to leave the murder in the script but that he asked for revisions to reflect demonstrators' concerns. `` The hero says that the murder is absolutely the wrong solution,'' said Singer. `` No one watching it could think we were condoning this by any stretch of the imagination.''
