<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct 22-23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Sees Benefit, and Danger, in Buyout Binge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT header coding.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The takeover-buyout mania now sweeping through corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has some Wall Streeters applauding and others shaking their heads. The fans of these multibillion-dollar deals say they are powerful medicine for a stock market still struggling to recover from the crash of 1987. In the absence of buying by individuals and many institutional money managers, they ask, where would the stock market be today without the leveraged-buyout specialists and the traders, known as arbitragers, who follow in their wake? What's more, they say, takeovers and buyouts are a long-term plus for the market because they reduce the supply of stock in the marketplace, giving an upward bias to the prices of the shares that remain available. But more skeptical observers, while acknowledging some of those points, argue that all this wheeling and dealing is contributing huge new amounts to an already dangerous accumulation of debt in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. And the activity it generates in the market, they say, represents unhealthy speculation rather than stable, long-term investment. The mergers and acquisitions binge is nothing new, of course. Takeovers and buyouts were a dominant force in the 1982-87 bull market. A similar phenomenon occurred in the 1960s, when conglomerate-building was the financial rage. Lately, however, the game has been played on an expanded scale. In the past week alone, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> proposed an $ 11.4 billion offer for <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabsico </ORGANIZATION> said it was considering a $ 17.6 billion management buyout plan. If such deals can be done, analysts say, there appears to be virtually no limit to what might be attempted in the future, no company too big to be ruled out as a takeover or buyout candidate. That prospect helped propel stock prices higher in the past week. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 50.32 to 2,183.50, hitting its highest levels since the crash of'87 as the first anniversary of that debacle passed. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite index gained 3.96 to 159.42; the <ORGANIZATION> NASDAQ </ORGANIZATION> composite index for the over-the-counter market added 4.00 to 388.59, and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> market value index was up 3.52 at 306.07. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> averaged 170.63 million shares a day, up from 147.05 million the week before. `` The short-term rewards to selling shareholders in the form of capital gains are indisputable,'' analysts at <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, observed in a recent appraisal of the mergers-and-acquisitions craze But `` the longer-term effects of takeovers are less healthy for the economy and for equity investors generally.'' Excessive debt-leveraging of corporate assets makes companies more vulnerable in the event of a recession, the report said. `` In fact, there is the potential that defaults arising from high debt service requirements for companies with reduced cash flows will even aggravate the economy's troubles, when the next recession comes. `` Although industry consolidations and restructurings may often be useful for strengthening the competitive edge in global markets, the transformation of billions of dollars of equity into debt is eroding the financial footings of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry. `` Market volatility and instability have increased as a result of the takeover wave, with the effect of driving many individual investors out of the stock market for years to come, if not for good,'' it said. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> noted that the greatest takeover wave in history was a basic cause of the stock market decline last October. The collapse was as severe as it was `` precisely because the takeover wave had pushed stock prices to artificially high levels,'' the report said. `` For that reason alone,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> concluded, `` one should find little comfort in the continuing high level of takeover activity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 22-23</NOTE>
