<HEAD>Control Of Futures Markets Remains Unresolved Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
commodity price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 One year after Black Monday, the question of which government agency should oversee the financial futures markets remains unresolved, a fact highlighted this past week at a gathering of futures industry leaders and regulators in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. A number of other crash-related issues also overhang the nation's futures and options exchanges, but none arouses a more emotional response among futures industry leaders than the control question, especially among officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest futures exchanges. Futures and options trading is regulated by the 14-year-old Commodities and <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Trading of stocks and bonds is regulated by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, set up in 1934 as part of the New Deal. Despite the undeniable link between the stock market and stock-index futures _ which can be used for either hedging stock positions or speculating on stock-market movements _ the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> exchanges have strongly opposed post-crash proposals that one agency should regulate both markets. Instead, they have argued for the creation of an agency that would coordinate sharing of trading information among all the financial markets. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in January to enlarge his agency's jurisdiction to give it `` direct regulatory authority'' over stock-index futures and any new futures contracts related to stocks. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Thursday, <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> took a more lenient stance, saying post-crash efforts to better coordinate the activities of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> and the markets were working satisfactorily. `` Nonetheless,'' <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, `` I continue to believe that in the long term there needs to be an ability to look beyond the parochial concerns of each of the separate stock and futures markets. In the long run, unified jurisdiction over these increasingly linked and unified markets will prove to be desirable.'' Earlier in the day, while sitting on a discussion panel with <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> Chairwoman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> and four futures industry leaders, <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> was even more conciliatory on the issue, saying that `` contrary to many press reports, I do not regard that as a very serious matter.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON>, who also sat on the panel, expressed his position bluntly: `` I do n't think you need a single regulator to create cooperation.'' Ms. <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointee who has been in office less than eight months, did not comment on the control issue but focused instead on the likelihood of increased regulation of futures trading under a <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is a Democrat and most of the bills introduced in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the past year proposing greater regulation of the futures markets were sponsored by Democrats. But Ms. <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> said she expected Republican Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to win the November election. The big question, she said, was whether <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would be willing to veto any futures-related legislation backed by a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> likely to be dominated by Democrats. The issue of regulatory jurisdiction over financial futures could come to a head next year when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must vote on reauthorizing the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> for another four years. By law, the agency dies next year unless reauthorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
