<FIRST>r f AM-RefineryCutbacks     10-22 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refinery Cutbacks,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chevron USA Plans 400 Fewer Jobs at Port Arthur Refinery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, citing increased competition and reduced profit, announced plans Friday to cut the workforce at its largest refinery by about 400 jobs. Company officials said a portion of the jobs will be eliminated through attrition and early retirement. The 4,000-acre plant was purchased by the <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary in 1984 from <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>, and employs more than 2,200 people. `` <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> has announced plans to streamline the refinery operations and the organization here to make the refinery more competitive _ and not only to make it more competitive, but to assure its continued operation,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>. The exact number of layoffs will not be known until company officials meet with union leaders to discuss the changes, he said, but <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> plans to operate the plant with about 400 fewer employees. `` Any announcement involving a reduction in manpower is difficult, but this has come as something of a relief to many of our Port Arthur business people because it means that <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> has decided to keep the plant open,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. A company task force had presented four options to improve refining operation profits, including the possibility of shutting down the plant, or reducing the workforce by more than half, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> sasid. `` This was the best of the -LRB- task force -RRB- alternatives,'' he said. `` It's a relief that we did not have to go to the big numbers.'' The changes were prompted, in part, by continuing volatility in the energy industry, he said. `` It relates to the extremely competitive market in which this refinery functions,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. `` This Gulf Coast region is the most competitive petroleum products market in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` We have not been competitive in this market for a long time.'' Smaller Chevron refining operations in <LOCATION> Pascagoula </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION> have proven more profitable, he said. The Port Arthur refinery is the largest owned by <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>, with an operating capacity off 407,000 barrels of crude per day. After streamlining, which is expected to begin immediately, ready capacity will be about 329,000 barrels per day, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. `` We've never run 400,000 barrels a day here,'' he said. A renewed marketing strategy calls for the refinery to place a greater emphasis on the production of petrochemicals, premium unleaded gasoline and lubricating base oils, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. The plant is one of few along the gulf coast with its own packaging facilities. The company plans to complete the cutbacks by the end of the first quarter 1989, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. The Port Arthur refinery first opened in 1901 and has undergone numerous renovations, including a $ 600-million improvement project in 1980, he said.
</TEXT>
