<HEAD>Knight-Ridder's Profit Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday its third-quarter profit fell 4.4 percent from a year ago, due mainly to weak retail advertising and lower ad revenue. For the three-month period ended Sept. 30, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s after-tax profit totaled $ 31.99 million, or 57 cents a share, down from $ 33.4 million, or 57 cents a share, in the year-ago period The latest quarter's net included $ 2.19 million from discontinued operations. Earlier this month, the company announced plans to sell its eight television stations. The media company's third quarter revenue rose 5.8 percent to $ 503.1 million from $ 475.6 million. `` A lower tax rate and the benefits of the repurchase of our own stock helped our earnings per share results during the quarter,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>, senior vice president and chief financial officer. `` Revenue growth from newspaper operations was a disappointing 3.2 percent. Retail and general advertising, mirroring nationwide trends, were both below our expectations,'' <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> said. For the first nine months, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s profit totaled $ 110.79 million, up 5.4 percent from $ 105.11 million in the same period in 1987. Revenue totaled $ 1.51 billion, up 4.8 percent from $ 1.44 billion in the year-earlier period.
