<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip in Skittish Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil prices declined in skittish trading as two <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> committees continued meetings about the cartel's overproduction The December contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, fell 9 cents Friday to close at $ 14.37 a 42-gallon barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Several other contract months fell by similar amounts. Trading was nervous, although less volatile than in sessions earlier this week. The November contract for <ORGANIZATION> WTI </ORGANIZATION>, which expired on Thursday, dropped 60 cents on Tuesday, soared 79 cents on Wednesday and then tumbled 80 cents in its final day. Oil futures have traveled a rocky road in recent weeks because of rampant overproduction by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> and hopes that the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> committees meeting in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> might make progress toward limiting the cartel's output Little concrete news came out of the gathering's first two days. The pricing and long-term strategy committees ended a second day of talks Friday with no announcement, and scheduled another round for Saturday. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Rilwanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON> said Friday progress toward a new production agreement rested on ironing out sharp differences between <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s current ceiling for 12 of its 13 member nations is 15.06 million barrels a day, although current production is estimated at close to 21 million barrels a day. As trading wore on Friday, `` every time a different report of a news story came out, -LRB- the market -RRB- would make a big move,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The market's headline-driven,'' he said. Refined products traded on the Mercantile Exchange were mixed. The November contract for home heating oil slipped 0.35 cent to close at 42.71 cents a gallon. But prices for wholesale unleaded gasoline surged higher because of tight supplies, <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON> said. The November contract for gasoline rose 1.87 cents to settle at 51.22 cents a gallon. <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON> called gasoline trading `` a different world by itself.''
